t for knowledge and academic work. Some of these institutions are: \n*[[Federal University of Petroleum Resources Effurun|Federal University of Petroleum Resources, Effurun]]\n*[[Delta State University, Abraka|Delta State University]]\n*[[Delta State Polytechnic]]s (three different Polytechnics, one at Oghara, one at Ogwashi-Uku and another at Ozoro)\n*The Film and Broadcast Academy, Ozoro\n*College of Education (two different state colleges, one at [[Agbor]] and another at [[Warri]]).\n*Federal College of Education Technical, [[Asaba, Delta|Asaba]]\n*College of Education, Mosogar\n*Delta State College of Health Technology, [[Ughelli]]\n*[[Petroleum Training Institute]], [[Effurun]]<ref>http://www.edusbaze.com/tag/www-pti-edu-ng/</ref>\n*[[Western Delta University]], [[Oghara]]\n*Novena University, Ogume-Amai\n*National Open University of Nigeria (three study centres, one at Asaba, one at [[Emevor]] and another at [[Owhrode]]).\n*Delta State School of Marine Technology, Burutu\n*Nigerian Maritime University, Okerenkoko, [[Warri]]\n*Conarina School of Maritime & Transport Technology, Oria-[[Abraka]]\n*University of Information and Communication Technology, [[Agbor]]\n*State School of Midwifery, [[Asaba, Delta|Asaba]]\n*School of Nursing (two schools, one at [[Agbor]] and another at [[Warri]])\n*Baptist School of Nursing, [[Eku]]\n*Edwin Clark University, Kiagbodo\n*Eagle Heights University, Omadino, Warri\n*Admiralty University of Nigeria at [[Ibusa]] and [[Sapele]]\n\n== Tourist attractions ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2017}}\nDelta State has some historical, cultural and socio-political tourist centers that attract visitors from around the globe. Some of these sites of tourism include:\n* '''The Nana's Palace''' built by Chief [[Nana Olomu]] of Ebrohim. He was a powerful 19th century indigenous entrepreneur who traded with the British. The relationship eventually turned sour. Later, he surrendered (not without putting up a fight) and was exiled to Ghana. His personal effects are housed in this grand palace.\n* '''The River Ethiope '''which is reputed to be the deepest inland waterway in Africa (at 176&nbsp;km). Its source is at the foot of a giant silk-cotton tree at Umuaja in Ukwuani Local Government Area of the state and flows through seven Local Government Areas in the State. It is a place of worship for Olokun traditional religion and also a common site for faithfuls of the [[Igbe religion|Igbe Religious Movement]].\n* '''The Araya Bible Site '''which houses a copy of the [[Holy Bible]]. It is believed that the bible descended to this spot miraculously from heaven around August, 1914. The bible dropped on rain-soaked yam and it didn't get wet. The site now attracts thousands of Christians yearly.\n* '''Demas Nwoko Edifice '''which was built using traditional materials, designs and construction techniques of the Igbo civilization and the Benin Empire by [[Demas Nwoko]], an architect, builder and artist of international repute from Idumuje-Ugboko, in Aniocha North Local Government Area, Delta State.\n* '''The Mungo Park House''' which is now the site of the National Museum, [[Asaba, Delta|Asaba]]. The house was constructed by the Royal Niger Company (RNC) in 1886 and was used as a colonial administrative headquarters, a military house, the colonial administrative divisional headquarters, the RNC Constabulary building,  and the seat of the Urban District Council at different times.\n* The '''[[River Niger Bridge (Onitsha)|Niger Bridge]]''' which connects Delta State (by extension, western Nigeria) to the Eastern part of Nigeria. It is a beauty to behold. It was completed in 1965 and cost \u00a35 million. It was damaged during the civil war, but later repaired.\n* '''Lander Brothers Anchorage, Asaba''' which was built in memory of early British explorers. The complex has a museum, a graveyard, and many artworks and writings. It houses a replica of one of the boats that was used by the brothers.\n* '''Falcorp Mangrove Park'''\n* '''Warri Kingdom Royal Cemetery''' which is 512 year old burial ground and serves as the resting place of past rulers of Warri kingdom. A tree is planted on each grave.\n\n==Sports==\nDelta State is known to have produced several sportsmen and women, notably [[Stephen Keshi|Stephen Okechukwu Keshi]], [[Sunday Oliseh]], Austin [[Jay-Jay Okocha]], [[Wilson Oruma]], [[Efetobore Sodje]] [[Blessing Okagbare]] and [[Jonathan Akpoborie]], [[Cindy Ofili]].\n\n==Notable people==\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n*[[Abel Ubeku]], first black Managing Director of Guinness Nigeria Plc.\n*[[Alibaba Akpobome]], stand up comedian and actor\n*[[Amaju Pinnick]], president of the Nigeria Football Federation\n*[[Ayo Oritsejafor]], founder of Word of Life Bible Church\n*[[Ben Okri]], writer\n*[[Blessing Okagbare]], athlete, [[Summer Olympics|Olympic]] and [[World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]] medalist in the long jump, and a world medallist in the [[200 metres]]\n*[[Bovi]], popular Nigerian comedian\n*[[Bruce Onobrakpeya]], 2006 UNESCO Living Human Treasure Award, trustee of Western Niger Delta University\n*[[David Dafinone]], Renowned Account/Politician\n*[[Dennis Osadebay]]\n*[[Dominic Oneya]]\n*[[Emmanuel Ibe Kachikwu]], Minister of State, Petroleum Resources, Nigeria.\n*[[Emmanuel Uduaghan]]\n*[[Enebeli Elebuwa]], Nigeria Actor\n*[[Gamaliel Onosode]]\n*[[Harrysong]]\n*[[I Go Dye]], popular comedian across Africa and [[United Nations]]' [[Millennium Development Goals]] Ambassador\n*[[Igho Sanomi]], Nigerian businessman\n*[[James Ibori]], former governor of Delta State\n*[[Jay-Jay Okocha|Okocha]], former Super Eagles Captain\n*[[Jeremiah Omoto Fufeyin]], founder of Christ Mercyland Deliverance Ministry\n*[[Jim Ovia]] \n*[[J. P. Clark|John Pepper Clark]], first professor of English in Africa, poet and writer\n*[[Joy Ogwu]], former Permanent Representative of Nigeria to the [[United Nations]].\n*[[Lynxxx]]\n*[[Michael Ashikodi Agbamuche]], former Attorney General & Minister for Justice of Nigeria\n*[[Michael Ibru]], business leader\n*[[Ngozi Okonjo-Iweala]]\n*[[Olorogun O'tega Emerhor]], Nigerian financial industry leader and politician.\n*[[Omawumi]], popular Nigerian entertainer.\n*[[Onigu Otite|Prof Onigu Otite]], sociologist and anthropologist\n*[[Orezi]]\n*[[Ovie Omo-Agege]]\n*[[Patrick Utomi]]\n*[[Paul Dike]], Past Chief of Defence Staff.\n*[[Richard Mofe-Damijo]], veteran actor\n*[[SHiiKANE]]\n*[[Stephen Keshi]]\n*[[Stephen Oru]]\n*[[Sunday Oliseh|Sunday Ogochukwu Oliseh]], Football Manager and former player\n*[[Sunny Ofehe]], international human & environmental rights activist.\n*[[Tanure Ojaide]], professor of English and renowned writer\n*[[Tony Elumelu]], [[United Bank for Africa|UBA]] and [[Heirs Holdings]].\n*[[Udoka Azubuike]], college basketball player at the [[University of Kansas]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Played Profile|url=http://kuathletics.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=8612|website=KUAtletics.com|date = 2016-04-14}}</ref>\n*[[Zulu Sofola]]\n\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666--->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.deltastate.gov.ng/ Delta State Government]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111007021024/http://www.emmanueluduaghan.com.ng/ Governor of Delta State]\n* [http://ikaweekly.com/ Delta State Newspaper]\n\n{{portalbar|Nigeria}}\n{{DeltaStateGovernors}}\n{{Nigeria states}}\n\n[[Category:Delta State| ]]\n[[Category:States of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Niger River Delta]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1991]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Rv breaking wikilinks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delta_State"}
{"title_page": "Siamosaurus", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Simosaurus}}{{short description|Potentially dubious genus of spinosaurid theropod dinosaur}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], ([[Barremian]]-[[Aptian]]) {{Fossilrange|129.4|113}}\n| image = Siamosaurus_tooth_by_PaleoGeek.png\n| image_caption = Illustrated [[holotype]] tooth, with [[Penny (British decimal coin)|British penny]] for scale\n| taxon = Siamosaurus\n| authority = Buffetaut & Ingavat, 1986\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = *'''''S. suteethorni''''' <small>Buffetaut & Ingavat, 1986 ([[type species|type]])</small>\n| synonyms = *'''''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'''''? <small>Hou, Yeh & Zhao, 1975</small>\n}}\n'''''Siamosaurus''''' (meaning \"Siamese lizard\") is a potentially [[Dubious name|dubious]] [[genus]] of [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived sometime between 129.4 to 113 million years ago, during the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Period (geologic time)|Period]] of what is now [[Isan|northeastern]] [[Thailand]]. It is the first spinosaurid reported from Asia is confidently known only from tooth [[Fossil|fossils]]; the first of which were found in the [[Sao Khua Formation]], with more teeth later recovered from the younger [[Khok Kruat Formation]]. The [[type species]] '''''Siamosaurus suteethorni''''', whose name honours Thai [[palaeontologist]] [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], was formally described in [[1986 in paleontology|1986]]. One possible ''Siamosaurus'' tooth was discovered in the Japanese [[Sebayashi Formation]] in 1994, and a tooth similar to it was found at the same site in 2015. In 2009, four teeth from China's [[Xinlong Formation]] were assigned to the spinosaurid species '''\"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis''''', which may be the same animal as ''Siamosaurus''. Fragmentary skeletal material from Thailand has been tentatively attributed to ''Siamosaurus'', as two partial spinosaurid skeletons have been found in Thailand, one in the Sao Khua and the other in the Khok Kruat Formation, but whether they belong to ''Siamosaurus'' or not is unclear.\n\nThe [[holotype]] tooth is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} long and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm|}} wide at the base. Since it is a tooth taxon, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s body size and weight are uncertain, though it has been estimated at between {{Convert|5.1 to 9.1|m||abbr=}} and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}. ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s teeth were straight, oval to circular in cross section, and lined with distinct lengthwise ridges. The tooth's [[Tooth enamel|enamel]] was wrinkled, similar to that of teeth from the related genus ''[[Baryonyx]]''. ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s identity has been questioned by many palaeontologists, who argue that its teeth are too similar to those of contemporaneous aquatic reptiles for it to be confidently classed as a dinosaur. Other researchers, who agree that the teeth are spinosaur in origin, deem them too similar to those of other Early Cretaceous spinosaurs to unequivocally raise a new genus. Based on characteristics of their teeth, ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' have been placed in the [[Spinosaurinae]] [[subfamily]].\n\nLike all spinosaurids, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth were conical, with reduced or absent [[Serration|serrations]]. This made them suitable for impaling rather than tearing flesh, a trait typically seen in largely [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) animals. Its relatives are known to have also consumed [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]] and small to medium-sized dinosaurs, and there is fossil evidence of ''Siamosaurus'' eating [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] dinosaurs, either via scavenging or hunting. ''Siamosaurus'' lived in a [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] habitat of [[Floodplain|floodplains]] and meandering rivers, where it coexisted with other theropod, sauropod, and (in at least the Khok Kruat Formation) [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontian]] dinosaurs. [[Isotope analysis]] indicates spinosaurids may have had [[semiaquatic]] habits, and ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s role as a piscivorous predator might have reduced the prominence of contemporaneous [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]] competing for the same food source.\n\n== History of discovery ==\n[[File:Cretaceous_strata_in_northeast_and_southeastern_Thailand.png|thumb|left|Geological map of the [[Khorat Plateau]] in northeast Thailand]]\n\nThe [[Sao Khua Formation]], where the first ''Siamosaurus'' [[Fossil|fossils]] were discovered, is part of the [[Khorat Group]].<ref name=\":0\">Buffetaut, E.; and Ingevat, R. (1986). Unusual theropod dinosaur teeth from the Upper Jurassic of Phu Wiang, northeastern Thailand. Rev. Paleobiol. 5: 217-220.</ref> The formation is dated to the [[Barremian]] [[Stage (geology)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Geological period|Period]], 129.4 to 125 million years ago,<ref name=\":15\" /> though it was formerly believed to be [[Late Jurassic]] in age.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Racey|first=Andrew|last2=G. S. Goodall|first2=J|date=2009|title=Palynology and stratigraphy of the Mesozoic Khorat Group red bed sequences from Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/249552008|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|volume=315|issue=1|pages=69\u201383|bibcode=2009GSLSP.315...69R|citeseerx=10.1.1.1030.8425|doi=10.1144/SP315.6|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|last=Bertin|first=Tor|date=2010|title=A catalogue of material and review of the Spinosauridae|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/235679976|journal=PalArch's Journal of Vertebrate Palaeontology|volume=7|pages=|via=}}</ref> Out of all [[Mesozoic]] formations in northeastern Thailand, the Sao Khua is the most abundant and diversified in [[vertebrate]] fossil discoveries.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> The Khorat Group exhibits taxa only of continental origin, with no definitive evidence for marine fossils or [[Sedimentary rock|sedimentary]] structures found so far. In 1963, Yoshitsugu Kobayashi of the [[Hokkaido University]] reported ichthyosaur and [[Plesiosauria|plesiosaur]] teeth from the Sao Khua Formation, but these have now been identified as belonging to ''Siamosaurus'' and a [[Crocodilia|crocodilian]] respectively.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/books/book/1678/late-palaeozoic-and-mesozoic-continental|title=Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Continental Ecosystems in SE Asia|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Cuny|first2=Gilles|date=2009|publisher=Geological Society of London|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=2018-06-11|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Suteethorn|first4=Varavudh}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, French [[Paleontologists|palaeontologist]] [[Eric Buffetaut|\u00c9ric Buffetaut]] and his Thai colleague Rucha Ingavat described a set of fossil teeth recovered from the Phu Pratu Teema locality of the Sao Khua Formation, in [[Khon Kaen Province]]. They reached no conclusion as to what animal they originated from, their opinion being that the specimens belonged \"either to an unusual [[Theropoda|theropod]] [[dinosaur]], or to some unknown crocodilian\". In [[1986 in paleontology|1986]], a reassessment of the remains by the same authors attributed them to a new [[genus]] and [[species]] of [[spinosaurid]] theropod, which they named ''Siamosaurus suteethorni''. The generic name alludes to the ancient name of Thailand, \"Siam\", while the specific name honours Thai [[geologist]] and palaeontologist [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], and his contributions to vertebrate palaeontology discoveries in Thailand.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:Museum_Dinosaur_KK.jpg|thumb|The [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]] houses [[fossil]] replicas and a sculpture of ''Siamosaurus''<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Boonchai|first=N|last2=Grote|first2=Paul|last3=Jintasakul|first3=P|date=2009-01-01|title=Paleontological parks and museums and prominent fossil sites in Thailand and their importance in the conservation of fossils|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/286206751|journal=PaleoParks - the Protection and Conservation of Fossil Sites Worldwide|pages=75\u201395}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|last=Karnjanatawe|first=Karnjana|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1264683/centre-of-the-northeast|title=Centre of the Northeast|date=2017|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\n\nThe best-preserved specimen from the series, designated DMR TF 2043a, was chosen as the [[holotype]] of ''Siamosaurus.<ref name=\":0\" />'' The [[Paratype|paratypes]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Siamosaurussuteethorni|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=Mickey|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> comprise eight other well-preserved teeth catalogued as DMR TF 2043b to i. The original fossils are currently housed in the palaeontological collection of the [[Department of Mineral Resources (Thailand)|Department of Mineral Resources]], [[Bangkok]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Other Thai fossils later referred to the taxon, including two well preserved teeth (SM2016-1-147 and SM2016-1-165) and one [[Cervical vertebrae|cervical]] (neck) [[vertebra]] (SM2016-1-067) are stored in the [[Sirindhorn Museum]], [[Kalasin Province]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219641|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219713|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219621|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> Isolated ''Siamosaurus'' teeth are common in the Sao Khua Formation.<ref name=\":1\" /> Sculptures of the animal have been erected in various places across northeastern Thailand, including Si Wiang Dinosaur Park,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mekloy|first=Pongpet|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1137381/jurassic-park-vs-the-weekend-warrior|title=Jurassic Park vs the weekend warrior|date=2016|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Siam Paragon]] shopping mall in Bangkok,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mekloy|first=Pongpet|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/formerly-one-of-the-biggest-smiles-in-the-land-of-smiles|title=Formerly one of the biggest smiles in the Land of Smiles|date=2017|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Phataranawik|first=Phatarawadee|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/life/Dinosaurs-in-the-big-city-30273487.html|title=Dinosaurs in the big city - The Nation|date=2015|work=The Nation|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> and the [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]].<ref name=\":10\" /> The animal was also illustrated on Thai postage stamps released in 1997, along with fellow Thai dinosaurs ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]] sirindhornae,'' ''[[Siamotyrannus]] isanensis'', and ''[[Psittacosaurus]] sattayaraki''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/scott2002standar00scot_1|title=Scott 2002 standard postage stamp catalogue. Volume 6 : countries of the world, So-Z|last=Scott Publishing Co|date=2001|publisher=Sidney, OH : Scott Pub. Co.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Khok_Kruat_spinosaurid_neural_spine.png|thumb|left|upright=0.60|Illustrated [[neural spine]] of a [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] from the [[Khok Kruat Formation]]]]\n\n''Siamosaurus'' is the first reported spinosaurid dinosaur from Asia,<ref name=\":14\" /> and subsequently to its naming, material resembling or possibly belonging to the taxon has been found across the continent. In 1975, Chinese palaeontologist Hou Lian-Hai and colleagues described five teeth as a new species of the [[Pliosauroidea|pliosauroid]] ''[[Sinopliosaurus]]'', which they named ''S. fusuiensis''.<ref>Hou, L., Yeh, H. and Zhao, X. (1975). Fossil reptiles from Fusui, Kwangshi. ''Vertebrata PalAsiatica'' 13; 24-33</ref> Four of these teeth (one was not found in the museum collection) were reassigned by Buffetaut and colleagues in 2008 to a ''Siamosaurus''-like taxon and referred to as [[\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis|\"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'']]''.'' The researchers deemed \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' as \"closely related to, if not identical with\" ''Siamosaurus suteethorni.<ref name=\"EBetal082\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360}}</ref>'' American palaeontologist Mickey Mortimer informally placed \"''S.''\" ''fusuiensis'' under the latter genus as a tentative additional species, ''Siamosaurus fusuiensis'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Sinopliosaurusfusuiensis|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=M.|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref> an analysis also held by Spanish palaeontologists Rub\u00e9n Molina-P\u00e9rez and Asier Larramendi in 2016.''<ref name=\":20\" />'' In 2019, it was referred by Thai palaeontologist Wongko Kamonlak and colleagues as ''Siamosaurus sp''. (of uncertain species).''<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Wongko|first=Kamonlak|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Khamha|first3=Suchada|last4=Lauprasert|first4=Komsorn|date=2019-03-31|title=Spinosaurid theropod teeth from the Red Beds of the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://li01.tci-thaijo.org/index.php/tnh/article/view/181194|journal=Tropical Natural History|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=8\u201320|issn=2586-9892}}</ref>'' Later in 2019, Thai palaeontologist Adun Samathi and colleagues considered the teeth as belonging to an indeterminate spinosaurid.<ref name=\":22\" /> The specimens were collected from China's Early Cretaceous [[Xinlong Formation]], in which spinosaurid teeth are frequently reported, though most of them are hard to differentiate from those of Japan or Thailand without further fossil material''.''<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite journal|last=MO|first=JINYOU|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|last4=Amiot|first4=Romain|last5=Cavin|first5=Lionel|last6=Cuny|first6=Gilles|last7=Suteethorn|first7=Varavudh|last8=SUTEETHORN|first8=SURAVECH|last9=JIANG|first9=SHAN|date=2015-07-02|title=Early Cretaceous vertebrates from the Xinlong Formation of Guangxi (southern China): A review|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/279805233|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=-1|pages=143\u2013159|doi=10.1017/S0016756815000394}}</ref> Buffetaut and Suteethorn suggested that the Xinlong Formation could be related to the Sao Khua or Khok Kruat Formations, since similar types of fossils have been recovered in these regions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|date=1999|title=The dinosaur fauna of the Sao Khua Formation of Thailand and the beginning of the Cretaceous radiation of dinosaurs in Asia|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018299000048|journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|language=en|volume=150|issue=1\u20132|pages=13\u201323|bibcode=1999PPP...150...13B|doi=10.1016/S0031-0182(99)00004-8|issn=0031-0182|via=}}</ref> Other spinosaurid teeth have been recovered from central China<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/271967379|title=A probable Baryonychine (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) tooth from the Upper Cretaceous of Henan Province, China|last=Hone|first=David|last2=Xu|first2=Xing|date=2010|website=ResearchGate|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-19|last3=Wang|first3=Deyou}}</ref> and [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2014/02/140224204737.htm|title=First discovery of dinosaur fossils in Malaysia|last=|first=|date=2014|access-date=2018-10-25|publisher=ResearchSEA|language=en|via=ScienceDaily}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, an isolated tooth (specimen [[Gunma Museum of Natural History|GMNH]]-PV-999) was found by a fossil prospector in the [[Sebayashi Formation]], Japan. The tooth was believed to belong to a [[marine reptile]] until 2003, when Japanese palaeontologist Yoshikazu Hasegawa and colleagues referred it to ?''Siamosaurus sp.'' (of uncertain species).<ref name=\":4\" /> The tooth came from rocks dated to the Barremian, similar in age to sediments that ''Siamosaurus'' teeth have been recovered from in Thailand.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Hasegawa|first=Y|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Manabe|first3=M|last4=Takakuwa|first4=Yuji|date=2003-03-01|title=A possible spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Gunma, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/313142817|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=7|pages=1\u20135}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> In 2015, a more incomplete tooth was recovered from the same formation by two local children. Kept under the specimen number KDC-PV-0003, the tooth was assigned to an indeterminate spinosaurid in 2017 by Japanese palaeontologist Kubota Katsuhiro and colleagues.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Katsuhiro|first=Kubota|last2=Takakuwa|first2=Yuji|last3=Yoshikazu|first3=Hasegawa|date=2017-03-31|title=Second discovery of a spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Kanna Town, Gunma Prefecture, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/317368894|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=01}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Phu_Wiang_Spinosaurid_Skeletal_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|Skeletal diagram and estimated size of \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\" compared to a human]]\n\nThailand's [[Khok Kruat Formation]] assumes a younger ([[Aptian]]; 125 to 113 million years old) age than the Sao Khua Formation,<ref name=\":12\" /> and has provided many spinosaurid teeth, including ones from ''Siamosaurus''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002-09-01|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.miketaylor.org.uk/dino/pubs/svpca2005/SVPCA2005Abstracts.pdf|title=53rd Symposium of Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy|last=Ahlberg|first=P.E.|last2=Blom|first2=H.|last3=Brazeau|first3=M.D.|last4=Anderson|first4=P.|publisher=The Natural History Museum|year=2005|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Khansubha|first4=Sasa-On|last5=Tong|first5=Haiyan|last6=Wongko|first6=K|date=2005-01-01|title=The dinosaur fauna from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) of Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/312976683|journal=Proceedings of the International Conference on Geology, Geotechnology and Mineral Resources of Indochina|pages=575\u2013581}}</ref> Given the varied size and [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]] of the teeth found, the presence of multiple spinosaur taxa in the region is likely.''<ref name=\":24\" />''<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/252320809|title=Program and Abstracts. 9th Annual Meeting of the European Association of Vertebrate Palaeontologists, Heraklion, Crete, 14-19 June 2011|last=van der Geer|first=Alexandra|last2=Athanassiou|first2=Athanassios|date=2011-01-01}}</ref> Eight of these teeth were described in detail by Kamonlak and colleagues in 2019, and classified into two main [[Morphotype|morphotypes]], the Khok Kruat morphotype, which is found only in the Khok Kruat Formation, and the ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype, which has been widely recovered from both the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations.''<ref name=\":24\" />'' \n\nIn 2004, excavation began on a partial skeleton from an outcrop of the Khok Kruat Formation near the city of [[Khon Kaen]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|title=52nd Symposium for Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy and the 13th meeting of the Symposium for Palaeontological Preparation and Conservation|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|publisher=University of Leicester & New Walk Museum|year=2004|isbn=|location=Leicester|pages=}}</ref> The specimen (SM-KK 14) consists of cervical and [[Dorsal vertebrae|dorsal]] (back) vertebrae, a {{Convert|60|cm||adj=on}} high [[neural spine]], [[pelvis]] (hip) fragments, a possible [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#metacarpals|metacarpal]] (long bone of the hand), and a [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#Chevron|chevron]]. The cervical vertebrae and pelvic region resemble those of the European spinosaur ''[[Baryonyx]]'', and the neural spine is elongated, similarly to those of other spinosaurids.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=Adun|last2=Chanthasit|first2=Phornphen|last3=Sander|first3=Paul Martin|date=2019-07-01|title=A review of theropod dinosaurs from the Late Jurassic to mid-Cretaceous of Southeast Asia|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396919300151|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|series=Palaeobiodiversity of Southeast Asia, issue 1|language=en|volume=105|issue=3|pages=201\u2013215|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2019.03.003|issn=0753-3969}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Angela|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Suteethorn|first3=Varavudh|date=2007|title=A tall-spined spinosaurid theropod from Thailand and the biogeography of spinosaurs|url=http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Future-Past-Meetings/MeetingPdfs/JVP_07.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume='''27''' (supplement 3)|pages=118A|via=}}</ref> A ''Siamosaurus'' tooth found nearby indicates the skeleton may belong to this genus, though this could also represent a scavenging event.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|displayauthors=etal|date=2004|title=Asian spinosaur confirmed|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|journal=SVPCA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In 2019, a series of spinosaurid [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#caudals|caudal]] (tail) vertebrae possibly belonging to ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' were recovered from the Sao Khua Formation, and described in a dissertation by Samathi. The fossils (SM-PW9B-11 to 17, SM-PW9B, SM-PW9A-unnumbered, SM-PW9-unnumbered, and SM 2017-1-176) were designated by Samathi as \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\", and bear similarities to ''[[Camarillasaurus]]'' and a ''Baryonyx'' specimen discovered in Portugal.<ref name=\":23\">Adun Samathi (2019) CHAPTER 6: \"A Spinosaurid from Thailand and the Reassessment of ''Camarillasaurus'' from the Early Cretaceous of Spain\" in [http://hss.ulb.uni-bonn.de/2019/5605/5605.pdf THEROPOD DINOSAURS FROM THAILAND AND SOUTHEAST ASIA PHYLOGENY, EVOLUTION, AND PALEOBIOGEOGRAPHY] Dissertation Thesis, University of Bonn pp.161-181</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n\nIn 2004, [[Don Lessem]] estimated ''Siamosaurus'' at {{Convert|9.1|m||abbr=}} long.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lessem|first=Don|url=http://archive.org/details/scholasticdinosa00less|title=Scholastic dinosaurs A to Z : the ultimate dinosaur encyclopedia|last2=Sovak|first2=Jan|last3=Scholastic Reference (Firm)|date=2004|publisher=New York : Scholastic|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> In 2005, Sussana Davidson and colleagues gave a lower estimate of {{Convert|8|m||abbr=}} in length and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/usborneinternetl00susa|title=The Usborne Internet-linked World atlas of dinosaurs|last=Davidson|first=Susanna|last2=Turnbull|first2=Stephanie|last3=Firth|first3=Rachel|last4=Rey|first4=Luis V.|last5=Slane|first5=Andrea|last6=Naish|first6=Darren|last7=Martill|first7=David M.|last8=Usborne Publishing Ltd|date=2005|publisher=New York : Scholastic Inc.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> And in 2016, Molina-P\u00e9rez and Larramendi estimated it at approximately {{convert|5.1|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|1.45|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall at the hips and weighing {{convert|255|kg|lb}}.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite book|last=Molina-Per\u00e9z & Larramendi|title=R\u00e9cords y curiosidades de los dinosaurios Ter\u00f3podos y otros dinosauromorfos|publisher=Larousse|year=2016|isbn=9780565094973|location=Barcelona, Spain|pages=275}}</ref> However, reliable calculations on the weight and body size of fragmentary dinosaurs like ''Siamosaurus'' are hindered by the lack of good material, such as a skull or body fossil.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\" was calculated as approximately {{convert|5|m|ft|abbr=on}} long by Samathi in 2019.<ref name=\":23\" /> \n\n=== Type specimens ===\n[[File:Asian_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Diagram comparing the [[holotype]] tooth (first from left) with other spinosaurid teeth from Asia]]\n\nFossil theropod teeth are typically identified by attributes such as the proportions, size, and curvature of the [[Crown (tooth)|crown]], as well as the presence and/or shape of the [[Denticle (tooth feature)|denticles]] (serrations).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Joshua B.|last2=Vann|first2=David R.|last3=Dodson|first3=Peter|date=2005|title=Dental morphology and variation in theropod dinosaurs: Implications for the taxonomic identification of isolated teeth|journal=The Anatomical Record Part A: Discoveries in Molecular, Cellular, and Evolutionary Biology|language=en|volume=285A|issue=2|pages=699\u2013736|doi=10.1002/ar.a.20206|pmid=15986487|issn=1552-4884}}</ref> The holotype of ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' (specimen DMR TF 2043a) is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} in total length, with the crown being {{Convert|47.7|mm|}} long, and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm|}} wide at its base. The tooth is relatively straight, with only minor front to back curvature. It is oval in cross section while other specimens are nearly circular in this aspect. Unlike in most theropods, the carinae (edges) of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth lack well-defined serrations. Some teeth (including the holotype) have a wave-like double recurvature when viewed front to back, which Buffetaut and Ingavat compared to that seen in [[Carnosauria|carnosaur]] teeth from the same formation and one ''[[Deinonychus]]'' tooth described by [[John Ostrom]] in 1969. The ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype is symmetrically concave front to back, and bears 15 flutes (lengthwise ridges) on its [[Glossary of dentistry#lingual|lingual]] (the side that faces the tongue) and [[Glossary of dentistry#labial|labial]] (outward facing) surfaces. These flutes run from the base of the crown before stopping {{Convert|5|mm|}} from the rounded tooth tip. A region of the holotype where the [[Tooth enamel|enamel]] (outer layer of the teeth) has weathered away reveals that these flutes extend down to the [[Dentin|dentine]] (second layer of the teeth).<ref name=\":0\" /> The enamel also has a granular (finely wrinkled) texture, as seen in teeth from ''Baryonyx''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2007|title=The spinosaurid dinosaur Baryonyx (Saurischia, Theropoda) in the Early Cretaceous of Portugal|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/geological-magazine/article/spinosaurid-dinosaur-baryonyx-saurischia-theropoda-in-the-early-cretaceous-of-portugal/E2F9B7C099506CE2CD948E022FBDAD5E|journal=Geological Magazine|language=en|volume=144|issue=6|pages=1021\u20131025|doi=10.1017/S0016756807003883|bibcode=2007GeoM..144.1021B|issn=1469-5081|via=}}</ref> Some of the [[Tooth root|root]] is preserved in the holotype and, as in all theropods, there is a large pocket for the tooth [[Pulp (tooth)|pulp]], which would have housed blood vessels and nerves. The holotype is among the larger teeth discovered by Buffetaut and Ingavat, one much smaller specimen (DMR TF 2043b) measures {{Convert|24.3|mm|}} in length. According to the authors, this dramatic size range suggests the teeth are from individuals of different ages.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Khok Kruat teeth ===\n[[File:Siamosaurus.jpg|thumb|Speculative life [[Paleoart|restoration]] of ''Siamosaurus'' based on relatives]]\n\nOf the two Khok Kruat Formation tooth morphotypes described by Kamonlak and colleagues in 2019, morphotype I, the Khok Kruat morphotype, is on average {{Convert|46.35|mm||abbr=}} in total length, of which the crown takes up {{Convert|43.77|mm||abbr=}}, with a {{Convert|18.40 by 13.5|mm||abbr=}} wide base. They are oval in cross section, have well defined carinae, and a smooth enamel surface, which becomes wrinkled at the base of the crown. They bear fine, sharply defined flutes, of which there are about 21 to 32 on each side. Morphotype II, the ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype, is on average {{Convert|51.25|mm||abbr=}} long, with a {{Convert|48.30|mm||abbr=}} tall crown that is {{Convert|17.30  by 14.65|mm||abbr=}} wide at the base. They are also oval in cross section and have distinct carinae, but unlike the Khok Kruat morphotype, the entire length of the crown has wrinkled enamel, and the flutes are coarser and fewer in number, with 11 to 16 on each side. The ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype also shares with ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'', GMNH-PV-999, and IVPP V 4793 a wrinkled enamel surface, and between 12 to 15 flutes on each side.''<ref name=\":24\" />''\n\n=== Possible material ===\n[[File:Sebayashi_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Partial tooth of an indeterminate spinosaurid (KDC-PV-0003) and possible ''Siamosaurus'' tooth (GMNH-PV-999), in the [[National Museum of Nature and Science]], Tokyo]]\n\nThe first Sebayashi Formation specimen (GMNH-PV-999) is an isolated tooth crown with a partially intact root. It is unknown on which jaw the tooth was positioned nor which surface faced the inside or outside of the mouth. The tooth's front and back carinae are well-defined, though the former is not well preserved. Besides having a broader, {{Convert|20 by 14|mm||adj=on}} wide base and being slightly smaller at {{Convert|51|mm|}} in length, GMNH-PV-999 has a very similar morphology to the ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype. Features shared between the two specimens include: a straight and only slightly compressed shape; a somewhat oval cross section; no serrations on the carinae (possibly due to bad preservation); and a flutes on the crown surface, the Japan specimen having 12 on each side. The specimens also share a crown surface with numerous small granular structures oriented parallel to their lengths. Because of these resemblances, Hasegawa and colleagues regarded GMNH-PV-999 as nearly identical to DMR TF 2043a.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nKDC-PV-0003, the second tooth found in the Sebayashi Formation, consists of a slightly recurved crown fragment with a preserved length of {{Convert|10|mm|}}. At its base, the crown is {{Convert|7.4|mm|}} long and {{Convert|6.8|mm|}} wide, with an almost circular cross section. Though less complete than the former specimens, KDC-PV-0003 exhibits better preservation of small details such as visible serrations, although poorly defined ones. The denticles, of which there are two to three every {{Convert|1|mm||adj=on}}, are visible only on the front carinae, due to the rear of the tooth being obscured by rock [[Matrix (geology)|matrix]]. A {{Convert|5.5|mm||adj=on}} long gap at the fossil's base exposes the dentine, which is covered in a {{Convert|1.6|mm||adj=on}} thick layer of enamel. The little that is preserved of KDC-PV-0003 shows that like the first Sebayashi Formation tooth, it has a granular texture and a minimum of 12 flutes on its surface, not all of which stretch to the full length of the crown. The granular structures of KDC-PV-0003 are sharper than in GMNH-PV-999. The interdenticle sulci (tiny furrows near the gaps between each denticle) of KDC-PV-0003 have an [[Oblique angle|oblique]] orientation of 45 degrees, exactly like those seen in GMNH-PV-999.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOut of the four teeth referred to \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'', specimen [[IVPP]] V 4793 is the most intact, although still somewhat deformed. The crown, which is missing its tip, is {{Convert|69|mm|}} long and {{Convert|16.5 by 13|mm|}} wide at the base. The tooth is straight, only slightly recurved, and has an oval cross section. The front and rear carinae are distinct, though their serrations have been heavily eroded, similar to those of KDC-PV-0003. Like the Thailand and Japan teeth, the \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' specimens bear developed flutes and a granular surface. As in both Sebayashi Formation teeth, there are 12 flutes on each face of \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis''{{'}}s teeth. Like in KDC-PV-0003, these flutes are of varied lengths. Buffetaut and colleagues likened the \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' teeth most to those of ''Siamosaurus'', given their identical crown shape, fluting, and granular enamel.<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />\n\n== Classification ==\n[[File:Spinosaurus_sp_Marocco_Cenom.JPG|thumb|Tooth of the related genus ''[[Spinosaurus]]'', Museo di Storia Naturale A. Stoppani, [[Lombardy]]]]\n\nIn 1986, Buffetaut and Ingavat classified ''Siamosaurus'' as a theropod because of the straight tall crown and double lateral recurvature of its teeth. At the time, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s particular combination of dental characteristics, especially the longitudinal fluting and lack of serrations, had not been observed in other theropods. The authors noted similarities in ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth to those of [[Ceratosauria|ceratosaurian]] tooth crowns, some of which also have longitudinal flutes. However, this identification was ruled out, since ceratosaur teeth differ in cross section, bear far fewer dental flutes, and have distinct serrations. Buffetaut and Suteethorn concluded that the closest taxon in dentition to ''Siamosaurus'' was ''Spinosaurus''. Like ''Siamosaurus,'' this African genus had straight and unserrated conical teeth, and though ''Spinosaurus'' lacked the developed flutes seen in ''Siamosaurus,'' Buffetaut and Ingavat noted that both smooth and fluted spinosaur teeth have been reported from Africa. Therefore, they tentatively placed ''Siamosaurus'' in the Spinosauridae [[Family (biology)|family]], based on close similarities in dentition to ''Spinosaurus aegyptiacus.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nMany palaeontologists have expressed skepticism towards Buffetaut and Ingavat's identification of ''Siamosaurus'', given that spinosaurid teeth, including many from Asia, have been time and again mistaken for those of aquatic reptiles like crocodilians, plesiosaurs, and ichthyosaurs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2010-01-01|title=Spinosaurs before Stromer: early finds of spinosaurid dinosaurs and their interpretations|url=http://sp.lyellcollection.org/content/343/1/175|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|language=en|volume=343|issue=1|pages=175\u2013188|bibcode=2010GSLSP.343..175B|doi=10.1144/SP343.10|issn=0305-8719}}</ref> In view of this, the German palaeontologist [[Hans-Dieter Sues]] and colleagues in 2002 argued that there is not enough material to confidently identify ''Siamosaurus'' as a dinosaur.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sues|first=Hans-Dieter|last2=Frey|first2=Eberhard|last3=Martill|first3=David M.|last4=Scott|first4=Diane M.|date=2002-09-19|title=Irritator challengeri, a spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Brazil|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|language=en|volume=22|issue=3|pages=535\u2013547|doi=10.1671/0272-4634(2002)022[0535:icasdt]2.0.co;2|issn=0272-4634}}</ref> In 2004, American palaeontologist [[Thomas Holtz]] and colleagues considered it a [[nomen dubium|''nomen dubium'']] (dubious name), stating that its teeth might instead belong to contemporaneous fish such as [[saurodontid]] or [[Ichthyodectidae|ichthyodectid]] [[Teleost|teleosts]].<ref name=\"HMC04\">Holtz Jr., T.R., Molnar, R.E., and Currie, P.J. (2004). \"Basal Tetanurae\". In: Weishampel, D.B., Dodson, P., and Osm\u00f3lska, H. (eds.), ''The Dinosauria'' (second edition). Berkeley: University of California Press:Berkeley, p. 71-110. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}</ref> The same year, American palaeontologist [[David Weishampel]] and colleagues placed ''Siamosaurus'' as an indeterminate theropod.<ref>{{Citation|last=Weishampel|first=David|title=Dinosaur Distribution|date=2004-06-12|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/234025996|pages=517\u2013606|access-date=2018-08-28|last2=Le Loeuff|first2=Jean|last3=Coria|first3=Rodolfo|last4=M. P. Gomani|first4=Elizabeth|last5=Zhao|first5=X|last6=Xu|first6=Xing|last7=Barrett|first7=Paul|last8=Sahni|first8=Ashok|last9=Noto|first9=Christopher}}</ref> And in 2012, an analysis by American palaeontologist Matthew Carrano and colleagues agreed with the possibility of confusion with other reptiles, and regarded the genus as a possible indeterminate spinosaur. They pointed out that oftentimes, isolated teeth are an unstable foundation for naming theropod taxa, and most species based on them turn out to be invalid.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Carrano|first=Matthew T.|last2=Benson|first2=Roger B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=Scott D.|date=2012-05-17|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|language=en|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927|issn=1477-2019}}</ref> This problem is especially common with spinosaurs, given that [[Cranium|cranial]] and skeletal fossils from the group are rare.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite journal|last=William Elliott HONE|first=David|last2=Richard HOLTZ|first2=Thomas|date=2017-06-01|title=A Century of Spinosaurs - A Review and Revision of the Spinosauridae with Comments on Their Ecology|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/318228524|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica - English Edition|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Plesiosaur_skull.jpg|thumb|left|Spinosaurid teeth are often mistaken for those of [[plesiosaurs]] (above) and vice versa, though there are certain differences between their dentition]]\n\nSome crocodilians have teeth with flutes similar to those in Asian spinosaurid teeth. However, crocodilian teeth are usually more strongly recurved than spinosaur teeth.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Crocodilians also lack the lateral double recurvature of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s tooth crowns, which, based on their shape, were probably vertically inserted into the jaw, whereas long-snouted crocodilian teeth are usually jut out from the mouth at an angle. Though ''Siamosaurus'' and plesiosaur teeth are similar in overall shape, Buffetaut and Ingavat point out that plesiosaurs have significantly more-recurved tooth crowns.<ref name=\":0\" /> Compared to plesiosaurs, Asian spinosaurid teeth also have coarser and more numerous flutes that extend almost the whole length of the crown.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />''<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2008, Buffetaut and colleagues noted that \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' teeth bear carinae on the plane of the crown's curvature, a condition not observed in plesiosaur teeth. The discovery of the Khok Kruat skeleton and of baryonychine teeth with dental flutes similar to those of ''Siamosaurus'', were also brought up by the researchers as further evidence of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s spinosaurid classification.''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />'' Later discoveries revealed that flutes and a lack or reduction of serrations were common characteristics of spinosaurid teeth.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Schultz|first2=Cesar L.|date=2017-11-06|title=Spinosaur taxonomy and evolution of craniodental features: Evidence from Brazil|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=12|issue=11|pages=e0187070|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187070|issn=1932-6203|pmc=5673194|pmid=29107966|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1287070S}}</ref><ref name=\":16\" /> \n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek.jpg|thumb|Restoration of ''[[Ichthyovenator]]'', a [[Spinosaurinae|spinosaurine]] from what is now Laos]]\n\nIn 2017, the Brazilian palaeontologists Marcos Sales and Cesar Schultz accepted ''Siamosaurus'' as a spinosaur, but stated that its teeth and those of \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' are too similar to those of other Cretaceous spinosaurids to unequivocally erect new taxa.<ref name=\":17\" /> Carrano and colleagues stated that the Khok Kruat skeleton may provide answers to their identification.<ref name=\":6\" /> Authors such as Milner and colleagues,<ref name=\":9\" /> Bertin Tor,<ref name=\":14\" /> Kamonlak Wongko and colleagues,<ref name=\":8\" /> and Thomas Holtz<ref name=\"Holtz2008\">{{cite book|title=Dinosaurs: The Most Complete, Up-to-Date Encyclopedia for Dinosaur Lovers of All Ages|last=Holtz|first=Thomas R. Jr.|date=2011|chapter=Winter 2010 Appendix|chapter-url=http://www.geol.umd.edu/~tholtz/dinoappendix/HoltzappendixWinter2010.pdf}}</ref> regarded the skeleton as first irrefutable evidence of spinosaurs in Asia. Nevertheless, in 2012 Ronan Allain and colleagues described the Laos spinosaurid ''[[Ichthyovenator]]'' and dubbed it \"The first definitive Asian spinosaurid\".<ref name=\"AXRK12\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref> Mickey Mortimer pointed out shortly after that even discounting teeth, the Khok Kruat skeleton was first mentioned eight years prior to ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s description.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dml.cmnh.org/2012Apr/msg00480.html|title=RE: Ichthyovenator, new spinosaurid from Early Cretaceous of Laos|website=dml.cmnh.org|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref> Sales and Shultz suggested that the various Asian teeth might eventually be attributed to ''Ichthyovenator''-like forms.<ref name=\":17\" /> In a 2014 abstract, Allain announced that three teeth from ''Ichthyovenator'' had been discovered, which typically of spinosaurines, bore straight and unserrated crowns. Though no comparison was made to the other Asian teeth.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Allain|first=Ronan|date=2014|title=New material of the theropod Ichthyovenator from Ban Kalum type locality (Laos): Implications for the synonymy of Spinosaurus and Sigilmassasaurus and the phylogeny of Spinosauridae|url=http://vertpaleo.org/GlobalPDFS/SVP-2014-Program-and-Abstract-Book-9-18-2014.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology Programs and Abstracts|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> A redescription of ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s validity as a genus is currently being prepared by Buffetaut.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nSpinosaurids were large [[Bipedalism|bipedal]] [[Carnivore|carnivores]] with well-built forelimbs and elongated, crocodile-like skulls. The [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] and [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] affinities of the group are subject to active research and debate, given that in comparison to other theropod groups, many of the family's taxa are based on poor fossil material.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Traditionally, the group is split into the [[subfamilies]] Spinosaurinae (unserrated, straight teeth with well marked flutes and more circular cross sections) and Baryonychinae (finely serrated, somewhat recurved teeth with weaker flutes and a more oval cross section). Since spinosaurines were, on average, larger animals than baryonychines, their teeth were also generally larger as well.<ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=\":16\" /> The morphological variation seen in spinosaurid teeth, however, shows that these characteristics are not always consistent within the subfamilies.<ref name=\":19\" /> The exact position of ''Siamosaurus'' within the Spinosauridae is difficult to determine, since as with most other Asian spinosaur teeth, no associated skulls or skeletons have been found for it.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002-09-01|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409}}</ref> In 2010, the British palaeontologist David Hone and colleagues referred ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' to the Spinosaurinae.<ref name=\":19\" /> Likewise, British palaeontologist Thomas Arden and colleagues resolved ''Siamosaurus'' as a basal member of the Spinosaurinae in 2019, their [[cladogram]] can be seen below.<ref name=\"arden2018\">{{cite journal|last=Arden|first=T.M.S.|last2=Klein|first2=C.G.|last3=Zouhri|first3=S.|last4=Longrich|first4=N.R.|year=2019|title=Aquatic adaptation in the skull of carnivorous dinosaurs (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) and the evolution of aquatic habits in ''Spinosaurus''|url=|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=93|pages=275\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2018.06.013}}</ref>\n\n{{clade|{{clade\n |1=Praia das Aguncheiras taxon\n |label2=[[Baryonychinae]]\n |2={{clade\n  |1=''[[Baryonyx walkeri]]'' [[File:Baryonyx_walkeri_restoration.jpg|middle|80px]]\n  |2=''[[Suchomimus tenerensis]]'' [[File:Suchomimustenerensis_(Flipped).png|middle|80px]] }}\n |label3=[[Spinosaurinae]]\n |3={{clade\n  |1='''''Siamosaurus suteethorni'''''\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=Eumeralla taxon\n   |2={{clade\n    |1=''[[Ichthyovenator laosensis]]'' [[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek_(Flipped).jpg|middle|77px]]\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Irritator challengeri]]'' [[File:Irritator Life Reconstruction.jpg|middle|80 px]]\n     |2=''[[Oxalaia quilombensis]]''\n     |label3=[[Spinosaurini]]\n     |3={{clade\n      |1=Gara Samani taxon\n      |2=''[[Sigilmassasaurus brevicollis]]''\n      |3=''[[Spinosaurus aegyptiacus]]'' [[File:Spinosaurus by Joschua Kn\u00fcppe.png|middle|80 px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}|style=font-size: 85%; line-height:85%;|label1=[[Spinosauridae]]}}\nLater in 2019, the Khok Kruat Formation teeth were also referred to the Spinosaurinae by Kamonlak and colleagues, on the basis that both the Khok Kruat and ''Siamosaurus'' morphotypes lack characteristics seen in baryonychines, such as long and slender roots, 0-10 flutes on each side, no well defined carinae, a sculptured surface of the crown base, and 45 degree orientation of the interdenticle sulci. But they share with spinosaurines a sub-circular to oval cross section, fluted tooth crowns, well defined front and rear carinae, distinct striations on the crown, varying denticle size, and a wrinkled surface on the crown base. The authors also noted that unlike spinosaurines such as ''[[Irritator]]'' and ''Spinosaurus'', Asian spinosaurines usually have more laterally compressed tooth crowns, and wrinkled enamel surface.''<ref name=\":24\" />''\n\n==Palaeobiology==\n\n=== Diet and feeding ===\nBuffetaut and Ingavat suggested in 1986 that ''Siamosaurus'', like other spinosaurids, probably led a heavily [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) lifestyle. Spinosaurids had highly specialised teeth better suited for piercing rather than tearing flesh, thanks to their long, conical tooth crowns with reduced or absent serrations. This dental morphology is also seen in plesiosaurs and long-snouted crocodilians.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\">{{Cite journal|last=Hone|first=David William Elliott|last2=Holtz|first2=Thomas Richard|date=June 2017|title=A century of spinosaurs \u2013 a review and revision of the Spinosauridae with comments on their ecology|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica \u2013 English Edition|language=en|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328|issn=1000-9515}}</ref> Though skull material from ''Siamosaurus'' is lacking, spinosaurs are known to have had low, narrow and elongated jaws with snout tips that fanned out into a [[Rosette (design)|rosette]]-like shape, similar to that of modern [[Gharial]]<nowiki/>s.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Fossil evidence shows that besides fish, spinosaurids also consumed pterosaurs and other dinosaurs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Martill|first2=David|last3=Escuilli\u00e9|first3=Fran\u00e7ois|date=2004-07-01|title=Pterosaurs as part of a spinosaur diet|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/430033a|journal=Nature|language=En|volume=429|issue=6995|pages=33|doi=10.1038/430033a|pmid=15229562|bibcode=2004Natur.429...33B|issn=0028-0836}}</ref> In the Sao Khua Formation, localities such as Wat Sakawan have yielded sauropod remains in association with tooth crowns from ''Siamosaurus'', documenting either predation or scavenging on part of the latter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n[[File:Spinosaurid_and_Kinnareemimus.PNG|thumb|Restoration of a generic spinosaur feeding on a [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] carcass in the [[Sao Khua Formation]] (''[[Kinnareemimus]]'' in the background), based on teeth belonging to ''Siamosaurus''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Lacerda|first2=Marcel B.|last3=Horn|first3=Bruno L. D.|last4=Oliveira|first4=Isabel A. P. de|last5=Schultz|first5=Cesar L.|date=2016-02-01|title=The \"\u03c7\" of the Matter: Testing the Relationship between Paleoenvironments and Three Theropod Clades|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=11|issue=2|pages=e0147031|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147031|pmid=26829315|pmc=4734717|issn=1932-6203|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147031S}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2006, Thai biologist Komsorn Lauprasert examined fossils collected from the Phu Kradung, Sao Khua, and Khok Kruat Formations. In this study, the teeth of ''Siamosaurus'' and a Morrocan spinosaurid were compared to those of crocodilians using [[Scanning electron microscope|scanning electron microscopy]]. Lauprasert found that spinosaurids and crocodilians may have employed similar feeding tactics and been under comparable [[Constraint (classical mechanics)|mechanical constraints]], based on resemblances in the [[microstructure]] of their tooth enamel. Lauprasert suggested that ''Siamosaurus'' could have therefore replaced the [[ecological niche]] of contemporaneous long-snouted crocodilians as a piscivorous predator. He notes that this likely occurred in correlation with the rising aridity of the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations during the Early Cretaceous, since ''Siamosaurus'' had better mobility in a dry environment than crocodilians did. This could explain the absence of long-snouted crocodilian fossils from that time and place.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite thesis|last=Lauprasert|first=Komsorn|title=Evolution and palaeoecology of crocodiles in the mesozoic of Khorat plateau, Thailand|date=2006|publisher=Chulalongkorn University|url=https://cuir.car.chula.ac.th/handle/123456789/14411|language=en}}</ref> A similar scenario was proposed for spinosaurids by Hone and colleagues in 2010, who noted that compared to large crocodilians and obligate aquatic predators, they could more easily travel from one body of water to another in search for prey.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n=== Aquatic habits ===\n\nA 2010 publication by French palaeontologist Romain Amiot and colleagues found that the [[isotopes of oxygen|oxygen isotope]] ratios of spinosaurid bones indicated [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles. Isotope ratios of spinosaurid teeth from various localities, including Thailand and China, were compared with isotopic compositions from contemporaneous theropods, turtles, and crocodilians. The study revealed that, among theropods, spinosaurid isotope ratios were closer to those of turtles and crocodilians. Thai spinosaurid teeth tended to have the largest difference from the ratios of other theropods, and those from Morocco tended to have the least difference. The authors concluded that spinosaurids, like modern crocodilians and hippopotamuses, spent much of their daily lives in or near water. They also suggested that semiaquatic habits and piscivory may explain how spinosaurids coexisted with other large theropods; by feeding on different prey items and occupying a distinct ecological niche, the different types of theropods would have been out of direct competition.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\"RMetal10\">{{cite journal |last=Amiot |first=R. |author2=Buffetaut, E. |author3=L\u00e9cuyer, C. |author4=Wang, X. |author5=Boudad, L. |author6=Ding, Z. |author7=Fourel, F. |author8=Hutt, S. |author9=Martineau, F. |author10=Medeiros, A. |author11=Mo, J. |author12=Simon, L. |author13=Suteethorn, V. |author14=Sweetman, S. |author15=Tong, H. |author16=Zhang, F. |author17=Zhou, Z. |year=2010 |title=Oxygen isotope evidence for semi-aquatic habits among spinosaurid theropods |journal=Geology |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=139\u2013142 |doi=10.1130/G30402.1|bibcode=2010Geo....38..139A }}</ref>\n\n== Palaeoenvironment and palaeobiogeography ==\n[[File:Sao_Khua_Formation_V2.png|thumb|left|Restoration of ''Siamosaurus'' hunting fish in the Sao Khua Formation, with a herd of ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]]'' in the background]]\n\nThe sediments of the Sao Khua Formation, composed of [[Red clay|red clays]], [[Mudstone|mudstones]], [[Sandstone|sandstones]], [[Siltstone|siltstones]] and [[Conglomerate (geology)|conglomerate]] rocks, record a [[fluvial]] environment dominated by lakes, [[Floodplain|floodplains]], and meandering low-energy rivers.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> This is consistent with the types of vertebrate fauna present in the formation, which comprise only terrestrial or freshwater animals, including dinosaurs, turtles, freshwater [[hybodont sharks]] and [[Actinopterygii|actinopterygian]] fishes, and the freshwater crocodilian ''[[Sunosuchus]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> Besides ''Siamosaurus'', there were dinosaurs like the [[Metriacanthosauridae|metriacanthosaurid]] ''Siamotyrannus isanensis'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carrano|first1=M. T.|last2=Benson|first2=R. B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=S. D.|date=2012|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927}}</ref> the [[Ornithomimosauria|ornithomimosaur]] ''[[Kinnareemimus]] khonkaenensis'',<ref name=\"description\">Buffetaut, E., Suteethorn, V. and Tong, H. (2009). \"An early 'ostrich dinosaur' (Theropoda: Ornithomimosauria) from the Early Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of NE Thailand\", pp. 229-243 IN E. Buffetaut, G. Cuny, J. Le Loeuff & V. Suteethorn (eds.), ''Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Ecosystems in SE Asia''. Geological Society, London, Special Publications 315: 229-243. {{doi|10.1144/SP315.16}}</ref> the [[Megaraptora|megaraptoran]] ''[[Phuwiangvenator]]'' ''yaemniyomi'', the basal [[Coelurosauria|coelurosaur]] ''[[Vayuraptor]]'' ''nongbualamphuensis,<ref name=\"Samathietal2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=A.|last2=Chanthasit|first2=P.|last3=Martin Sander|first3=P.|date=May 2019|title=Two new basal coelurosaurian theropod dinosaurs from the Lower Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of Thailand|journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica|language=en|volume=64|issue=2|pages=239\u2013260|doi=10.4202/app.00540.2018}}</ref>'' a ''[[Compsognathus]]''-like theropod, as well as sauropods like ''Phuwiangosaurus sirindhornae'' and two indeterminate forms. Sauropod remains are some of the most abundant in the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> No [[Ornithischia|ornithischian]] dinosaur fossils have been found in the Sao Khua Formation, possibly suggesting that they were uncommon compared to [[Saurischia|saurischian]] dinosaurs.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations had a more [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] climate than the older, more humid [[Phu Kradung Formation]].<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe Khok Kruat Formation is composed mostly of sandstones, conglomerates, siltstones, and [[Shale|shales]]. Similarly to the Sao Khua Formation, the deposition of these sediments occurred in an arid to semi-arid floodplain environment of slow-moving, meandering rivers.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=Jintasakul|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|last4=You|first4=Hai-Lu|date=2015|title=A New Basal Hadrosauroid Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation in Nakhon Ratchasima Province, Northeastern Thailand|url=|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=10|issue=12|pages=e0145904|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1045904S|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0145904|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4696827|pmid=26716981|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":12\" /> Vertebrates from the Khok Kruat assemblage include [[Semionotiformes|semionotiform]] fishes, hybodont sharks, turtles, dinosaurs, pterosaurs, and crocodilians. The dinosaur fauna of this ecosystem included the [[Carcharodontosauridae|carcharodontosaurid]] ''[[Siamraptor]]'' ''suwati'',''<ref name=\"Chokchaloemwong2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Chokchaloemwong|first=Duangsuda|last2=Hattori|first2=Soki|last3=Cuesta|first3=Elena|last4=Jintasakul|first4=Pratueng|last5=Shibata|first5=Masateru|last6=Azuma|first6=Yoichi|date=2019-10-09|editor-last=Liu|editor-first=Jun|title=A new carcharodontosaurian theropod (Dinosauria: Saurischia) from the Lower Cretaceous of Thailand|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=14|issue=10|pages=e0222489|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0222489|pmid=31596853|pmc=6784982|issn=1932-6203}}</ref>'' [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontians]] like ''[[Sirindhorna]] khoratensis'',<ref name=\":15\" /> ''[[Ratchasimasaurus]] suranaerae'',<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=JINTASAKUL|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|date=2011-10-01|title=A New Iguanodontian Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation, Nakhon Ratchasima in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/264655916|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica|volume=85|issue=5|pages=969\u2013976|doi=10.1111/j.1755-6724.2011.00530.x}}</ref> and ''[[Siamodon]] nimngami'';<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2011-01-01|title=A new iguanodontian dinosaur from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous, Aptian) of northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396911000425|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|language=en|volume=97|issue=1\u20132|pages=51\u201362|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2011.08.001|issn=0753-3969|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh}}</ref> as well as a ''Phuwiangosaurus''-like sauropod,<ref name=\":7\" /> an indeterminate [[Ceratopsia|ceratopsian]],<ref name=\"sereno2010\">{{cite book|title=New Perspectives on Horned Dinosaurs: The Royal Tyrrell Museum Ceratopsian Symposium|last=Sereno|first=Paul C.|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2010|editor1-last=Ryan|editor1-first=Michael J.|location=Bloomington and Indianapolis|pages=21\u201358|chapter=Taxonomy, cranial morphology, and relationships of parrot-beaked dinosaurs (Ceratopsia:''Psittacosaurus'')|editor2-last=Chinnery-Allgeier|editor2-first=Brenda J.|editor3-last=Eberth|editor3-first=David A.}}</ref> and various indeterminate theropods.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> The formation is probably equivalent to the [[Gres superieurs Formation]] of Laos, since animals like advanced iguanodontians, sauropods, and spinosaurids have also been found there.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\nIn 2010, American palaeontologist [[Stephen L. Brusatte|Stephen Brusatte]] and colleagues noted that the discovery of spinosaurids in Asia, a family previously known only from Europe, Africa, and South America, suggests faunal interchange between the [[Supercontinent|supercontinents]] [[Laurasia]] (in the north) and [[Gondwana]] (in the south) during the early Late Cretaceous. Though it may also be possible that spinosaurids already had a [[cosmopolitan distribution]] before the Middle Cretaceous, and thus preceding the breakup of Laurasia from Gondwana. However, the authors noted that more evidence is needed to test this hypothesis.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Brusatte|first=Stephen|last2=B. J. Benson|first2=R|last3=Xu|first3=Xing|date=2010-12-10|title=The evolution of large-bodied therood dinosaurs during the Mesozoic in Asia|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260714806|journal=Journal of Iberian Geology|volume=36|issue=2|pages=275\u2013296|doi=10.5209/rev_JIGE.2010.v36.n2.12}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n{{Megalosauroidea}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q134636}}\n\n[[Category:Spinosaurids]]\n[[Category:Barremian life]]\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1986]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by \u00c9ric Buffetaut]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Simosaurus}}{{short description|Potentially dubious genus of spinosaurid theropod dinosaur}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], ([[Barremian]]-[[Aptian]]) {{Fossilrange|129.4|113}}\n| image = Siamosaurus_tooth_by_PaleoGeek.png\n| image_caption = Illustrated [[holotype]] tooth, with [[Penny (British decimal coin)|British penny]] for scale\n| taxon = Siamosaurus\n| authority = Buffetaut & Ingavat, 1986\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = *'''''S. suteethorni''''' <small>Buffetaut & Ingavat, 1986 ([[type species|type]])</small>\n| synonyms = *'''''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'''''? <small>Hou, Yeh & Zhao, 1975</small>\n}}\n'''''Siamosaurus''''' (meaning \"Siamese lizard\") is a potentially [[Dubious name|dubious]] [[genus]] of [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived sometime between 129.4 to 113 million years ago, during the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Period (geologic time)|Period]] of what is now [[Isan|northeastern]] [[Thailand]]. It is the first spinosaurid reported from Asia is confidently known only from tooth [[Fossil|fossils]]; the first of which were found in the [[Sao Khua Formation]], with more teeth later recovered from the younger [[Khok Kruat Formation]]. The [[type species]] '''''Siamosaurus suteethorni''''', whose name honours Thai [[palaeontologist]] [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], was formally described in [[1986 in paleontology|1986]]. One possible ''Siamosaurus'' tooth was discovered in the Japanese [[Sebayashi Formation]] in 1994, and a tooth similar to it was found at the same site in 2015. In 2009, four teeth from China's [[Xinlong Formation]] were assigned to the spinosaurid species '''\"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis''''', which may be the same animal as ''Siamosaurus''. Fragmentary skeletal material from Thailand has been tentatively attributed to ''Siamosaurus'', asTwo partial spinosaurid skeletons have been found in Thailand, one in the Sao Khua and the other in the Khok Kruat Formation, but whether they belong to ''Siamosaurus'' or not is unclear.\n\nThe [[holotype]] tooth is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} long and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm|}} wide at the base. Since it is a tooth taxon, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s body size and weight are uncertain, though it has been estimated at between {{Convert|5.1 to 9.1|m||abbr=}} and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}. ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s teeth were straight, oval to circular in cross section, and lined with distinct lengthwise ridges. The tooth's [[Tooth enamel|enamel]] was wrinkled, similar to that of teeth from the related genus ''[[Baryonyx]]''. ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s identity has been questioned by many palaeontologists, who argue that its teeth are too similar to those of contemporaneous aquatic reptiles for it to be confidently classed as a dinosaur. Other researchers, who agree that the teeth are spinosaur in origin, deem them too similar to those of other Early Cretaceous spinosaurs to unequivocally raise a new genus. Based on characteristics of their teeth, ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' have been placed in the [[Spinosaurinae]] [[subfamily]].\n\nLike all spinosaurids, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth were conical, with reduced or absent [[Serration|serrations]]. This made them suitable for impaling rather than tearing flesh, a trait typically seen in largely [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) animals. Its relatives are known to have also consumed [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]] and small to medium-sized dinosaurs, and there is fossil evidence of ''Siamosaurus'' eating [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] dinosaurs, either via scavenging or hunting. ''Siamosaurus'' lived in a [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] habitat of [[Floodplain|floodplains]] and meandering rivers, where it coexisted with other theropod, sauropod, and (in at least the Khok Kruat Formation) [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontian]] dinosaurs. [[Isotope analysis]] indicates spinosaurids may have had [[semiaquatic]] habits, and ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s role as a piscivorous predator might have reduced the prominence of contemporaneous [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]] competing for the same food source.\n\n== History of discovery ==\n[[File:Cretaceous_strata_in_northeast_and_southeastern_Thailand.png|thumb|left|Geological map of the [[Khorat Plateau]] in northeast Thailand]]\n\nThe [[Sao Khua Formation]], where the first ''Siamosaurus'' [[Fossil|fossils]] were discovered, is part of the [[Khorat Group]].<ref name=\":0\">Buffetaut, E.; and Ingevat, R. (1986). Unusual theropod dinosaur teeth from the Upper Jurassic of Phu Wiang, northeastern Thailand. Rev. Paleobiol. 5: 217-220.</ref> The formation is dated to the [[Barremian]] [[Stage (geology)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Geological period|Period]], 129.4 to 125 million years ago,<ref name=\":15\" /> though it was formerly believed to be [[Late Jurassic]] in age.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Racey|first=Andrew|last2=G. S. Goodall|first2=J|date=2009|title=Palynology and stratigraphy of the Mesozoic Khorat Group red bed sequences from Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/249552008|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|volume=315|issue=1|pages=69\u201383|bibcode=2009GSLSP.315...69R|citeseerx=10.1.1.1030.8425|doi=10.1144/SP315.6|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|last=Bertin|first=Tor|date=2010|title=A catalogue of material and review of the Spinosauridae|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/235679976|journal=PalArch's Journal of Vertebrate Palaeontology|volume=7|pages=|via=}}</ref> Out of all [[Mesozoic]] formations in northeastern Thailand, the Sao Khua is the most abundant and diversified in [[vertebrate]] fossil discoveries.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> The Khorat Group exhibits taxa only of continental origin, with no definitive evidence for marine fossils or [[Sedimentary rock|sedimentary]] structures found so far. In 1963, Yoshitsugu Kobayashi of the [[Hokkaido University]] reported ichthyosaur and [[Plesiosauria|plesiosaur]] teeth from the Sao Khua Formation, but these have now been identified as belonging to ''Siamosaurus'' and a [[Crocodilia|crocodilian]] respectively.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/books/book/1678/late-palaeozoic-and-mesozoic-continental|title=Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Continental Ecosystems in SE Asia|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Cuny|first2=Gilles|date=2009|publisher=Geological Society of London|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=2018-06-11|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Suteethorn|first4=Varavudh}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, French [[Paleontologists|palaeontologist]] [[Eric Buffetaut|\u00c9ric Buffetaut]] and his Thai colleague Rucha Ingavat described a set of fossil teeth recovered from the Phu Pratu Teema locality of the Sao Khua Formation, in [[Khon Kaen Province]]. They reached no conclusion as to what animal they originated from, their opinion being that the specimens belonged \"either to an unusual [[Theropoda|theropod]] [[dinosaur]], or to some unknown crocodilian\". In [[1986 in paleontology|1986]], a reassessment of the remains by the same authors attributed them to a new [[genus]] and [[species]] of [[spinosaurid]] theropod, which they named ''Siamosaurus suteethorni''. The generic name alludes to the ancient name of Thailand, \"Siam\", while the specific name honours Thai [[geologist]] and palaeontologist [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], and his contributions to vertebrate palaeontology discoveries in Thailand.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:Museum_Dinosaur_KK.jpg|thumb|The [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]] houses [[fossil]] replicas and a sculpture of ''Siamosaurus''<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Boonchai|first=N|last2=Grote|first2=Paul|last3=Jintasakul|first3=P|date=2009-01-01|title=Paleontological parks and museums and prominent fossil sites in Thailand and their importance in the conservation of fossils|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/286206751|journal=PaleoParks - the Protection and Conservation of Fossil Sites Worldwide|pages=75\u201395}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|last=Karnjanatawe|first=Karnjana|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1264683/centre-of-the-northeast|title=Centre of the Northeast|date=2017|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\n\nThe best-preserved specimen from the series, designated DMR TF 2043a, was chosen as the [[holotype]] of ''Siamosaurus.<ref name=\":0\" />'' The [[Paratype|paratypes]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Siamosaurussuteethorni|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=Mickey|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> comprise eight other well-preserved teeth catalogued as DMR TF 2043b to i. The original fossils are currently housed in the palaeontological collection of the [[Department of Mineral Resources (Thailand)|Department of Mineral Resources]], [[Bangkok]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Other Thai fossils later referred to the taxon, including two well preserved teeth (SM2016-1-147 and SM2016-1-165) and one [[Cervical vertebrae|cervical]] (neck) [[vertebra]] (SM2016-1-067) are stored in the [[Sirindhorn Museum]], [[Kalasin Province]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219641|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219713|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219621|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> Isolated ''Siamosaurus'' teeth are common in the Sao Khua Formation.<ref name=\":1\" /> Sculptures of the animal have been erected in various places across northeastern Thailand, including Si Wiang Dinosaur Park,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mekloy|first=Pongpet|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1137381/jurassic-park-vs-the-weekend-warrior|title=Jurassic Park vs the weekend warrior|date=2016|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Siam Paragon]] shopping mall in Bangkok,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mekloy|first=Pongpet|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/formerly-one-of-the-biggest-smiles-in-the-land-of-smiles|title=Formerly one of the biggest smiles in the Land of Smiles|date=2017|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Phataranawik|first=Phatarawadee|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/life/Dinosaurs-in-the-big-city-30273487.html|title=Dinosaurs in the big city - The Nation|date=2015|work=The Nation|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> and the [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]].<ref name=\":10\" /> The animal was also illustrated on Thai postage stamps released in 1997, along with fellow Thai dinosaurs ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]] sirindhornae,'' ''[[Siamotyrannus]] isanensis'', and ''[[Psittacosaurus]] sattayaraki''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/scott2002standar00scot_1|title=Scott 2002 standard postage stamp catalogue. Volume 6 : countries of the world, So-Z|last=Scott Publishing Co|date=2001|publisher=Sidney, OH : Scott Pub. Co.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Khok_Kruat_spinosaurid_neural_spine.png|thumb|left|upright=0.60|Illustrated [[neural spine]] of a [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] from the [[Khok Kruat Formation]]]]\n\n''Siamosaurus'' is the first reported spinosaurid dinosaur from Asia,<ref name=\":14\" /> and subsequently to its naming, material resembling or possibly belonging to the taxon has been found across the continent. In 1975, Chinese palaeontologist Hou Lian-Hai and colleagues described five teeth as a new species of the [[Pliosauroidea|pliosauroid]] ''[[Sinopliosaurus]]'', which they named ''S. fusuiensis''.<ref>Hou, L., Yeh, H. and Zhao, X. (1975). Fossil reptiles from Fusui, Kwangshi. ''Vertebrata PalAsiatica'' 13; 24-33</ref> Four of these teeth (one was not found in the museum collection) were reassigned by Buffetaut and colleagues in 2008 to a ''Siamosaurus''-like taxon and referred to as [[\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis|\"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'']]''.'' The researchers deemed \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' as \"closely related to, if not identical with\" ''Siamosaurus suteethorni.<ref name=\"EBetal082\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360}}</ref>'' American palaeontologist Mickey Mortimer informally placed \"''S.''\" ''fusuiensis'' under the latter genus as a tentative additional species, ''Siamosaurus fusuiensis'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Sinopliosaurusfusuiensis|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=M.|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref> an analysis also held by Spanish palaeontologists Rub\u00e9n Molina-P\u00e9rez and Asier Larramendi in 2016.''<ref name=\":20\" />'' In 2019, it was referred by Thai palaeontologist Wongko Kamonlak and colleagues as ''Siamosaurus sp''. (of uncertain species).''<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Wongko|first=Kamonlak|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Khamha|first3=Suchada|last4=Lauprasert|first4=Komsorn|date=2019-03-31|title=Spinosaurid theropod teeth from the Red Beds of the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://li01.tci-thaijo.org/index.php/tnh/article/view/181194|journal=Tropical Natural History|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=8\u201320|issn=2586-9892}}</ref>'' Later in 2019, Thai palaeontologist Adun Samathi and colleagues considered the teeth as belonging to an indeterminate spinosaurid.<ref name=\":22\" /> The specimens were collected from China's Early Cretaceous [[Xinlong Formation]], in which spinosaurid teeth are frequently reported, though most of them are hard to differentiate from those of Japan or Thailand without further fossil material''.''<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite journal|last=MO|first=JINYOU|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|last4=Amiot|first4=Romain|last5=Cavin|first5=Lionel|last6=Cuny|first6=Gilles|last7=Suteethorn|first7=Varavudh|last8=SUTEETHORN|first8=SURAVECH|last9=JIANG|first9=SHAN|date=2015-07-02|title=Early Cretaceous vertebrates from the Xinlong Formation of Guangxi (southern China): A review|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/279805233|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=-1|pages=143\u2013159|doi=10.1017/S0016756815000394}}</ref> Buffetaut and Suteethorn suggested that the Xinlong Formation could be related to the Sao Khua or Khok Kruat Formations, since similar types of fossils have been recovered in these regions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|date=1999|title=The dinosaur fauna of the Sao Khua Formation of Thailand and the beginning of the Cretaceous radiation of dinosaurs in Asia|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018299000048|journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|language=en|volume=150|issue=1\u20132|pages=13\u201323|bibcode=1999PPP...150...13B|doi=10.1016/S0031-0182(99)00004-8|issn=0031-0182|via=}}</ref> Other spinosaurid teeth have been recovered from central China<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/271967379|title=A probable Baryonychine (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) tooth from the Upper Cretaceous of Henan Province, China|last=Hone|first=David|last2=Xu|first2=Xing|date=2010|website=ResearchGate|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-19|last3=Wang|first3=Deyou}}</ref> and [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2014/02/140224204737.htm|title=First discovery of dinosaur fossils in Malaysia|last=|first=|date=2014|access-date=2018-10-25|publisher=ResearchSEA|language=en|via=ScienceDaily}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, an isolated tooth (specimen [[Gunma Museum of Natural History|GMNH]]-PV-999) was found by a fossil prospector in the [[Sebayashi Formation]], Japan. The tooth was believed to belong to a [[marine reptile]] until 2003, when Japanese palaeontologist Yoshikazu Hasegawa and colleagues referred it to ?''Siamosaurus sp.'' (of uncertain species).<ref name=\":4\" /> The tooth came from rocks dated to the Barremian, similar in age to sediments that ''Siamosaurus'' teeth have been recovered from in Thailand.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Hasegawa|first=Y|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Manabe|first3=M|last4=Takakuwa|first4=Yuji|date=2003-03-01|title=A possible spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Gunma, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/313142817|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=7|pages=1\u20135}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> In 2015, a more incomplete tooth was recovered from the same formation by two local children. Kept under the specimen number KDC-PV-0003, the tooth was assigned to an indeterminate spinosaurid in 2017 by Japanese palaeontologist Kubota Katsuhiro and colleagues.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Katsuhiro|first=Kubota|last2=Takakuwa|first2=Yuji|last3=Yoshikazu|first3=Hasegawa|date=2017-03-31|title=Second discovery of a spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Kanna Town, Gunma Prefecture, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/317368894|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=01}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Phu_Wiang_Spinosaurid_Skeletal_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|Skeletal diagram and estimated size of \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\" compared to a human]]\n\nThailand's [[Khok Kruat Formation]] assumes a younger ([[Aptian]]; 125 to 113 million years old) age than the Sao Khua Formation,<ref name=\":12\" /> and has provided many spinosaurid teeth, including ones from ''Siamosaurus''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002-09-01|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.miketaylor.org.uk/dino/pubs/svpca2005/SVPCA2005Abstracts.pdf|title=53rd Symposium of Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy|last=Ahlberg|first=P.E.|last2=Blom|first2=H.|last3=Brazeau|first3=M.D.|last4=Anderson|first4=P.|publisher=The Natural History Museum|year=2005|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Khansubha|first4=Sasa-On|last5=Tong|first5=Haiyan|last6=Wongko|first6=K|date=2005-01-01|title=The dinosaur fauna from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) of Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/312976683|journal=Proceedings of the International Conference on Geology, Geotechnology and Mineral Resources of Indochina|pages=575\u2013581}}</ref> Given the varied size and [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]] of the teeth found, the presence of multiple spinosaur taxa in the region is likely.''<ref name=\":24\" />''<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/252320809|title=Program and Abstracts. 9th Annual Meeting of the European Association of Vertebrate Palaeontologists, Heraklion, Crete, 14-19 June 2011|last=van der Geer|first=Alexandra|last2=Athanassiou|first2=Athanassios|date=2011-01-01}}</ref> Eight of these teeth were described in detail by Kamonlak and colleagues in 2019, and classified into two main [[Morphotype|morphotypes]], the Khok Kruat morphotype, which is found only in the Khok Kruat Formation, and the ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype, which has been widely recovered from both the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations.''<ref name=\":24\" />'' \n\nIn 2004, excavation began on a partial skeleton from an outcrop of the Khok Kruat Formation near the city of [[Khon Kaen]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|title=52nd Symposium for Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy and the 13th meeting of the Symposium for Palaeontological Preparation and Conservation|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|publisher=University of Leicester & New Walk Museum|year=2004|isbn=|location=Leicester|pages=}}</ref> The specimen (SM-KK 14) consists of cervical and [[Dorsal vertebrae|dorsal]] (back) vertebrae, a {{Convert|60|cm||adj=on}} high [[neural spine]], [[pelvis]] (hip) fragments, a possible [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#metacarpals|metacarpal]] (long bone of the hand), and a [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#Chevron|chevron]]. The cervical vertebrae and pelvic region resemble those of the European spinosaur ''[[Baryonyx]]'', and the neural spine is elongated, similarly to those of other spinosaurids.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=Adun|last2=Chanthasit|first2=Phornphen|last3=Sander|first3=Paul Martin|date=2019-07-01|title=A review of theropod dinosaurs from the Late Jurassic to mid-Cretaceous of Southeast Asia|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396919300151|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|series=Palaeobiodiversity of Southeast Asia, issue 1|language=en|volume=105|issue=3|pages=201\u2013215|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2019.03.003|issn=0753-3969}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Angela|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Suteethorn|first3=Varavudh|date=2007|title=A tall-spined spinosaurid theropod from Thailand and the biogeography of spinosaurs|url=http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Future-Past-Meetings/MeetingPdfs/JVP_07.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume='''27''' (supplement 3)|pages=118A|via=}}</ref> A ''Siamosaurus'' tooth found nearby indicates the skeleton may belong to this genus, though this could also represent a scavenging event.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|displayauthors=etal|date=2004|title=Asian spinosaur confirmed|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|journal=SVPCA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In 2019, a series of spinosaurid [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#caudals|caudal]] (tail) vertebrae possibly belonging to ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' were recovered from the Sao Khua Formation, and described in a dissertation by Samathi. The fossils (SM-PW9B-11 to 17, SM-PW9B, SM-PW9A-unnumbered, SM-PW9-unnumbered, and SM 2017-1-176) were designated by Samathi as \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\", and bear similarities to ''[[Camarillasaurus]]'' and a ''Baryonyx'' specimen discovered in Portugal.<ref name=\":23\">Adun Samathi (2019) CHAPTER 6: \"A Spinosaurid from Thailand and the Reassessment of ''Camarillasaurus'' from the Early Cretaceous of Spain\" in [http://hss.ulb.uni-bonn.de/2019/5605/5605.pdf THEROPOD DINOSAURS FROM THAILAND AND SOUTHEAST ASIA PHYLOGENY, EVOLUTION, AND PALEOBIOGEOGRAPHY] Dissertation Thesis, University of Bonn pp.161-181</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n\nIn 2004, [[Don Lessem]] estimated ''Siamosaurus'' at {{Convert|9.1|m||abbr=}} long.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lessem|first=Don|url=http://archive.org/details/scholasticdinosa00less|title=Scholastic dinosaurs A to Z : the ultimate dinosaur encyclopedia|last2=Sovak|first2=Jan|last3=Scholastic Reference (Firm)|date=2004|publisher=New York : Scholastic|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> In 2005, Sussana Davidson and colleagues gave a lower estimate of {{Convert|8|m||abbr=}} in length and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/usborneinternetl00susa|title=The Usborne Internet-linked World atlas of dinosaurs|last=Davidson|first=Susanna|last2=Turnbull|first2=Stephanie|last3=Firth|first3=Rachel|last4=Rey|first4=Luis V.|last5=Slane|first5=Andrea|last6=Naish|first6=Darren|last7=Martill|first7=David M.|last8=Usborne Publishing Ltd|date=2005|publisher=New York : Scholastic Inc.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> And in 2016, Molina-P\u00e9rez and Larramendi estimated it at approximately {{convert|5.1|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|1.45|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall at the hips and weighing {{convert|255|kg|lb}}.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite book|last=Molina-Per\u00e9z & Larramendi|title=R\u00e9cords y curiosidades de los dinosaurios Ter\u00f3podos y otros dinosauromorfos|publisher=Larousse|year=2016|isbn=9780565094973|location=Barcelona, Spain|pages=275}}</ref> However, reliable calculations on the weight and body size of fragmentary dinosaurs like ''Siamosaurus'' are hindered by the lack of good material, such as a skull or body fossil.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\" was calculated as approximately {{convert|5|m|ft|abbr=on}} long by Samathi in 2019.<ref name=\":23\" /> \n\n=== Type specimens ===\n[[File:Asian_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Diagram comparing the [[holotype]] tooth (first from left) with other spinosaurid teeth from Asia]]\n\nFossil theropod teeth are typically identified by attributes such as the proportions, size, and curvature of the [[Crown (tooth)|crown]], as well as the presence and/or shape of the [[Denticle (tooth feature)|denticles]] (serrations).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Joshua B.|last2=Vann|first2=David R.|last3=Dodson|first3=Peter|date=2005|title=Dental morphology and variation in theropod dinosaurs: Implications for the taxonomic identification of isolated teeth|journal=The Anatomical Record Part A: Discoveries in Molecular, Cellular, and Evolutionary Biology|language=en|volume=285A|issue=2|pages=699\u2013736|doi=10.1002/ar.a.20206|pmid=15986487|issn=1552-4884}}</ref> The holotype of ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' (specimen DMR TF 2043a) is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} in total length, with the crown being {{Convert|47.7|mm|}} long, and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm|}} wide at its base. The tooth is relatively straight, with only minor front to back curvature. It is oval in cross section while other specimens are nearly circular in this aspect. Unlike in most theropods, the carinae (edges) of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth lack well-defined serrations. Some teeth (including the holotype) have a wave-like double recurvature when viewed front to back, which Buffetaut and Ingavat compared to that seen in [[Carnosauria|carnosaur]] teeth from the same formation and one ''[[Deinonychus]]'' tooth described by [[John Ostrom]] in 1969. The ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype is symmetrically concave front to back, and bears 15 flutes (lengthwise ridges) on its [[Glossary of dentistry#lingual|lingual]] (the side that faces the tongue) and [[Glossary of dentistry#labial|labial]] (outward facing) surfaces. These flutes run from the base of the crown before stopping {{Convert|5|mm|}} from the rounded tooth tip. A region of the holotype where the [[Tooth enamel|enamel]] (outer layer of the teeth) has weathered away reveals that these flutes extend down to the [[Dentin|dentine]] (second layer of the teeth).<ref name=\":0\" /> The enamel also has a granular (finely wrinkled) texture, as seen in teeth from ''Baryonyx''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2007|title=The spinosaurid dinosaur Baryonyx (Saurischia, Theropoda) in the Early Cretaceous of Portugal|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/geological-magazine/article/spinosaurid-dinosaur-baryonyx-saurischia-theropoda-in-the-early-cretaceous-of-portugal/E2F9B7C099506CE2CD948E022FBDAD5E|journal=Geological Magazine|language=en|volume=144|issue=6|pages=1021\u20131025|doi=10.1017/S0016756807003883|bibcode=2007GeoM..144.1021B|issn=1469-5081|via=}}</ref> Some of the [[Tooth root|root]] is preserved in the holotype and, as in all theropods, there is a large pocket for the tooth [[Pulp (tooth)|pulp]], which would have housed blood vessels and nerves. The holotype is among the larger teeth discovered by Buffetaut and Ingavat, one much smaller specimen (DMR TF 2043b) measures {{Convert|24.3|mm|}} in length. According to the authors, this dramatic size range suggests the teeth are from individuals of different ages.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Khok Kruat teeth ===\n[[File:Siamosaurus.jpg|thumb|Speculative life [[Paleoart|restoration]] of ''Siamosaurus'' based on relatives]]\n\nOf the two Khok Kruat Formation tooth morphotypes described by Kamonlak and colleagues in 2019, morphotype I, the Khok Kruat morphotype, is on average {{Convert|46.35|mm||abbr=}} in total length, of which the crown takes up {{Convert|43.77|mm||abbr=}}, with a {{Convert|18.40 by 13.5|mm||abbr=}} wide base. They are oval in cross section, have well defined carinae, and a smooth enamel surface, which becomes wrinkled at the base of the crown. They bear fine, sharply defined flutes, of which there are about 21 to 32 on each side. Morphotype II, the ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype, is on average {{Convert|51.25|mm||abbr=}} long, with a {{Convert|48.30|mm||abbr=}} tall crown that is {{Convert|17.30  by 14.65|mm||abbr=}} wide at the base. They are also oval in cross section and have distinct carinae, but unlike the Khok Kruat morphotype, the entire length of the crown has wrinkled enamel, and the flutes are coarser and fewer in number, with 11 to 16 on each side. The ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype also shares with ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'', GMNH-PV-999, and IVPP V 4793 a wrinkled enamel surface, and between 12 to 15 flutes on each side.''<ref name=\":24\" />''\n\n=== Possible material ===\n[[File:Sebayashi_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Partial tooth of an indeterminate spinosaurid (KDC-PV-0003) and possible ''Siamosaurus'' tooth (GMNH-PV-999), in the [[National Museum of Nature and Science]], Tokyo]]\n\nThe first Sebayashi Formation specimen (GMNH-PV-999) is an isolated tooth crown with a partially intact root. It is unknown on which jaw the tooth was positioned nor which surface faced the inside or outside of the mouth. The tooth's front and back carinae are well-defined, though the former is not well preserved. Besides having a broader, {{Convert|20 by 14|mm||adj=on}} wide base and being slightly smaller at {{Convert|51|mm|}} in length, GMNH-PV-999 has a very similar morphology to the ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype. Features shared between the two specimens include: a straight and only slightly compressed shape; a somewhat oval cross section; no serrations on the carinae (possibly due to bad preservation); and a flutes on the crown surface, the Japan specimen having 12 on each side. The specimens also share a crown surface with numerous small granular structures oriented parallel to their lengths. Because of these resemblances, Hasegawa and colleagues regarded GMNH-PV-999 as nearly identical to DMR TF 2043a.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nKDC-PV-0003, the second tooth found in the Sebayashi Formation, consists of a slightly recurved crown fragment with a preserved length of {{Convert|10|mm|}}. At its base, the crown is {{Convert|7.4|mm|}} long and {{Convert|6.8|mm|}} wide, with an almost circular cross section. Though less complete than the former specimens, KDC-PV-0003 exhibits better preservation of small details such as visible serrations, although poorly defined ones. The denticles, of which there are two to three every {{Convert|1|mm||adj=on}}, are visible only on the front carinae, due to the rear of the tooth being obscured by rock [[Matrix (geology)|matrix]]. A {{Convert|5.5|mm||adj=on}} long gap at the fossil's base exposes the dentine, which is covered in a {{Convert|1.6|mm||adj=on}} thick layer of enamel. The little that is preserved of KDC-PV-0003 shows that like the first Sebayashi Formation tooth, it has a granular texture and a minimum of 12 flutes on its surface, not all of which stretch to the full length of the crown. The granular structures of KDC-PV-0003 are sharper than in GMNH-PV-999. The interdenticle sulci (tiny furrows near the gaps between each denticle) of KDC-PV-0003 have an [[Oblique angle|oblique]] orientation of 45 degrees, exactly like those seen in GMNH-PV-999.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOut of the four teeth referred to \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'', specimen [[IVPP]] V 4793 is the most intact, although still somewhat deformed. The crown, which is missing its tip, is {{Convert|69|mm|}} long and {{Convert|16.5 by 13|mm|}} wide at the base. The tooth is straight, only slightly recurved, and has an oval cross section. The front and rear carinae are distinct, though their serrations have been heavily eroded, similar to those of KDC-PV-0003. Like the Thailand and Japan teeth, the \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' specimens bear developed flutes and a granular surface. As in both Sebayashi Formation teeth, there are 12 flutes on each face of \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis''{{'}}s teeth. Like in KDC-PV-0003, these flutes are of varied lengths. Buffetaut and colleagues likened the \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' teeth most to those of ''Siamosaurus'', given their identical crown shape, fluting, and granular enamel.<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />\n\n== Classification ==\n[[File:Spinosaurus_sp_Marocco_Cenom.JPG|thumb|Tooth of the related genus ''[[Spinosaurus]]'', Museo di Storia Naturale A. Stoppani, [[Lombardy]]]]\n\nIn 1986, Buffetaut and Ingavat classified ''Siamosaurus'' as a theropod because of the straight tall crown and double lateral recurvature of its teeth. At the time, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s particular combination of dental characteristics, especially the longitudinal fluting and lack of serrations, had not been observed in other theropods. The authors noted similarities in ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth to those of [[Ceratosauria|ceratosaurian]] tooth crowns, some of which also have longitudinal flutes. However, this identification was ruled out, since ceratosaur teeth differ in cross section, bear far fewer dental flutes, and have distinct serrations. Buffetaut and Suteethorn concluded that the closest taxon in dentition to ''Siamosaurus'' was ''Spinosaurus''. Like ''Siamosaurus,'' this African genus had straight and unserrated conical teeth, and though ''Spinosaurus'' lacked the developed flutes seen in ''Siamosaurus,'' Buffetaut and Ingavat noted that both smooth and fluted spinosaur teeth have been reported from Africa. Therefore, they tentatively placed ''Siamosaurus'' in the Spinosauridae [[Family (biology)|family]], based on close similarities in dentition to ''Spinosaurus aegyptiacus.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nMany palaeontologists have expressed skepticism towards Buffetaut and Ingavat's identification of ''Siamosaurus'', given that spinosaurid teeth, including many from Asia, have been time and again mistaken for those of aquatic reptiles like crocodilians, plesiosaurs, and ichthyosaurs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2010-01-01|title=Spinosaurs before Stromer: early finds of spinosaurid dinosaurs and their interpretations|url=http://sp.lyellcollection.org/content/343/1/175|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|language=en|volume=343|issue=1|pages=175\u2013188|bibcode=2010GSLSP.343..175B|doi=10.1144/SP343.10|issn=0305-8719}}</ref> In view of this, the German palaeontologist [[Hans-Dieter Sues]] and colleagues in 2002 argued that there is not enough material to confidently identify ''Siamosaurus'' as a dinosaur.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sues|first=Hans-Dieter|last2=Frey|first2=Eberhard|last3=Martill|first3=David M.|last4=Scott|first4=Diane M.|date=2002-09-19|title=Irritator challengeri, a spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Brazil|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|language=en|volume=22|issue=3|pages=535\u2013547|doi=10.1671/0272-4634(2002)022[0535:icasdt]2.0.co;2|issn=0272-4634}}</ref> In 2004, American palaeontologist [[Thomas Holtz]] and colleagues considered it a [[nomen dubium|''nomen dubium'']] (dubious name), stating that its teeth might instead belong to contemporaneous fish such as [[saurodontid]] or [[Ichthyodectidae|ichthyodectid]] [[Teleost|teleosts]].<ref name=\"HMC04\">Holtz Jr., T.R., Molnar, R.E., and Currie, P.J. (2004). \"Basal Tetanurae\". In: Weishampel, D.B., Dodson, P., and Osm\u00f3lska, H. (eds.), ''The Dinosauria'' (second edition). Berkeley: University of California Press:Berkeley, p. 71-110. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}</ref> The same year, American palaeontologist [[David Weishampel]] and colleagues placed ''Siamosaurus'' as an indeterminate theropod.<ref>{{Citation|last=Weishampel|first=David|title=Dinosaur Distribution|date=2004-06-12|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/234025996|pages=517\u2013606|access-date=2018-08-28|last2=Le Loeuff|first2=Jean|last3=Coria|first3=Rodolfo|last4=M. P. Gomani|first4=Elizabeth|last5=Zhao|first5=X|last6=Xu|first6=Xing|last7=Barrett|first7=Paul|last8=Sahni|first8=Ashok|last9=Noto|first9=Christopher}}</ref> And in 2012, an analysis by American palaeontologist Matthew Carrano and colleagues agreed with the possibility of confusion with other reptiles, and regarded the genus as a possible indeterminate spinosaur. They pointed out that oftentimes, isolated teeth are an unstable foundation for naming theropod taxa, and most species based on them turn out to be invalid.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Carrano|first=Matthew T.|last2=Benson|first2=Roger B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=Scott D.|date=2012-05-17|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|language=en|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927|issn=1477-2019}}</ref> This problem is especially common with spinosaurs, given that [[Cranium|cranial]] and skeletal fossils from the group are rare.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite journal|last=William Elliott HONE|first=David|last2=Richard HOLTZ|first2=Thomas|date=2017-06-01|title=A Century of Spinosaurs - A Review and Revision of the Spinosauridae with Comments on Their Ecology|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/318228524|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica - English Edition|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Plesiosaur_skull.jpg|thumb|left|Spinosaurid teeth are often mistaken for those of [[plesiosaurs]] (above) and vice versa, though there are certain differences between their dentition]]\n\nSome crocodilians have teeth with flutes similar to those in Asian spinosaurid teeth. However, crocodilian teeth are usually more strongly recurved than spinosaur teeth.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Crocodilians also lack the lateral double recurvature of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s tooth crowns, which, based on their shape, were probably vertically inserted into the jaw, whereas long-snouted crocodilian teeth are usually jut out from the mouth at an angle. Though ''Siamosaurus'' and plesiosaur teeth are similar in overall shape, Buffetaut and Ingavat point out that plesiosaurs have significantly more-recurved tooth crowns.<ref name=\":0\" /> Compared to plesiosaurs, Asian spinosaurid teeth also have coarser and more numerous flutes that extend almost the whole length of the crown.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />''<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2008, Buffetaut and colleagues noted that \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' teeth bear carinae on the plane of the crown's curvature, a condition not observed in plesiosaur teeth. The discovery of the Khok Kruat skeleton and of baryonychine teeth with dental flutes similar to those of ''Siamosaurus'', were also brought up by the researchers as further evidence of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s spinosaurid classification.''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />'' Later discoveries revealed that flutes and a lack or reduction of serrations were common characteristics of spinosaurid teeth.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Schultz|first2=Cesar L.|date=2017-11-06|title=Spinosaur taxonomy and evolution of craniodental features: Evidence from Brazil|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=12|issue=11|pages=e0187070|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187070|issn=1932-6203|pmc=5673194|pmid=29107966|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1287070S}}</ref><ref name=\":16\" /> \n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek.jpg|thumb|Restoration of ''[[Ichthyovenator]]'', a [[Spinosaurinae|spinosaurine]] from what is now Laos]]\n\nIn 2017, the Brazilian palaeontologists Marcos Sales and Cesar Schultz accepted ''Siamosaurus'' as a spinosaur, but stated that its teeth and those of \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' are too similar to those of other Cretaceous spinosaurids to unequivocally erect new taxa.<ref name=\":17\" /> Carrano and colleagues stated that the Khok Kruat skeleton may provide answers to their identification.<ref name=\":6\" /> Authors such as Milner and colleagues,<ref name=\":9\" /> Bertin Tor,<ref name=\":14\" /> Kamonlak Wongko and colleagues,<ref name=\":8\" /> and Thomas Holtz<ref name=\"Holtz2008\">{{cite book|title=Dinosaurs: The Most Complete, Up-to-Date Encyclopedia for Dinosaur Lovers of All Ages|last=Holtz|first=Thomas R. Jr.|date=2011|chapter=Winter 2010 Appendix|chapter-url=http://www.geol.umd.edu/~tholtz/dinoappendix/HoltzappendixWinter2010.pdf}}</ref> regarded the skeleton as first irrefutable evidence of spinosaurs in Asia. Nevertheless, in 2012 Ronan Allain and colleagues described the Laos spinosaurid ''[[Ichthyovenator]]'' and dubbed it \"The first definitive Asian spinosaurid\".<ref name=\"AXRK12\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref> Mickey Mortimer pointed out shortly after that even discounting teeth, the Khok Kruat skeleton was first mentioned eight years prior to ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s description.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dml.cmnh.org/2012Apr/msg00480.html|title=RE: Ichthyovenator, new spinosaurid from Early Cretaceous of Laos|website=dml.cmnh.org|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref> Sales and Shultz suggested that the various Asian teeth might eventually be attributed to ''Ichthyovenator''-like forms.<ref name=\":17\" /> In a 2014 abstract, Allain announced that three teeth from ''Ichthyovenator'' had been discovered, which typically of spinosaurines, bore straight and unserrated crowns. Though no comparison was made to the other Asian teeth.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Allain|first=Ronan|date=2014|title=New material of the theropod Ichthyovenator from Ban Kalum type locality (Laos): Implications for the synonymy of Spinosaurus and Sigilmassasaurus and the phylogeny of Spinosauridae|url=http://vertpaleo.org/GlobalPDFS/SVP-2014-Program-and-Abstract-Book-9-18-2014.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology Programs and Abstracts|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> A redescription of ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s validity as a genus is currently being prepared by Buffetaut.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nSpinosaurids were large [[Bipedalism|bipedal]] [[Carnivore|carnivores]] with well-built forelimbs and elongated, crocodile-like skulls. The [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] and [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] affinities of the group are subject to active research and debate, given that in comparison to other theropod groups, many of the family's taxa are based on poor fossil material.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Traditionally, the group is split into the [[subfamilies]] Spinosaurinae (unserrated, straight teeth with well marked flutes and more circular cross sections) and Baryonychinae (finely serrated, somewhat recurved teeth with weaker flutes and a more oval cross section). Since spinosaurines were, on average, larger animals than baryonychines, their teeth were also generally larger as well.<ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=\":16\" /> The morphological variation seen in spinosaurid teeth, however, shows that these characteristics are not always consistent within the subfamilies.<ref name=\":19\" /> The exact position of ''Siamosaurus'' within the Spinosauridae is difficult to determine, since as with most other Asian spinosaur teeth, no associated skulls or skeletons have been found for it.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002-09-01|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409}}</ref> In 2010, the British palaeontologist David Hone and colleagues referred ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' to the Spinosaurinae.<ref name=\":19\" /> Likewise, British palaeontologist Thomas Arden and colleagues resolved ''Siamosaurus'' as a basal member of the Spinosaurinae in 2019, their [[cladogram]] can be seen below.<ref name=\"arden2018\">{{cite journal|last=Arden|first=T.M.S.|last2=Klein|first2=C.G.|last3=Zouhri|first3=S.|last4=Longrich|first4=N.R.|year=2019|title=Aquatic adaptation in the skull of carnivorous dinosaurs (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) and the evolution of aquatic habits in ''Spinosaurus''|url=|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=93|pages=275\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2018.06.013}}</ref>\n\n{{clade|{{clade\n |1=Praia das Aguncheiras taxon\n |label2=[[Baryonychinae]]\n |2={{clade\n  |1=''[[Baryonyx walkeri]]'' [[File:Baryonyx_walkeri_restoration.jpg|middle|80px]]\n  |2=''[[Suchomimus tenerensis]]'' [[File:Suchomimustenerensis_(Flipped).png|middle|80px]] }}\n |label3=[[Spinosaurinae]]\n |3={{clade\n  |1='''''Siamosaurus suteethorni'''''\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=Eumeralla taxon\n   |2={{clade\n    |1=''[[Ichthyovenator laosensis]]'' [[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek_(Flipped).jpg|middle|77px]]\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Irritator challengeri]]'' [[File:Irritator Life Reconstruction.jpg|middle|80 px]]\n     |2=''[[Oxalaia quilombensis]]''\n     |label3=[[Spinosaurini]]\n     |3={{clade\n      |1=Gara Samani taxon\n      |2=''[[Sigilmassasaurus brevicollis]]''\n      |3=''[[Spinosaurus aegyptiacus]]'' [[File:Spinosaurus by Joschua Kn\u00fcppe.png|middle|80 px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}|style=font-size: 85%; line-height:85%;|label1=[[Spinosauridae]]}}\nLater in 2019, the Khok Kruat Formation teeth were also referred to the Spinosaurinae by Kamonlak and colleagues, on the basis that both the Khok Kruat and ''Siamosaurus'' morphotypes lack characteristics seen in baryonychines, such as long and slender roots, 0-10 flutes on each side, no well defined carinae, a sculptured surface of the crown base, and 45 degree orientation of the interdenticle sulci. But they share with spinosaurines a sub-circular to oval cross section, fluted tooth crowns, well defined front and rear carinae, distinct striations on the crown, varying denticle size, and a wrinkled surface on the crown base. The authors also noted that unlike spinosaurines such as ''[[Irritator]]'' and ''Spinosaurus'', Asian spinosaurines usually have more laterally compressed tooth crowns, and wrinkled enamel surface.''<ref name=\":24\" />''\n\n==Palaeobiology==\n\n=== Diet and feeding ===\nBuffetaut and Ingavat suggested in 1986 that ''Siamosaurus'', like other spinosaurids, probably led a heavily [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) lifestyle. Spinosaurids had highly specialised teeth better suited for piercing rather than tearing flesh, thanks to their long, conical tooth crowns with reduced or absent serrations. This dental morphology is also seen in plesiosaurs and long-snouted crocodilians.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\">{{Cite journal|last=Hone|first=David William Elliott|last2=Holtz|first2=Thomas Richard|date=June 2017|title=A century of spinosaurs \u2013 a review and revision of the Spinosauridae with comments on their ecology|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica \u2013 English Edition|language=en|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328|issn=1000-9515}}</ref> Though skull material from ''Siamosaurus'' is lacking, spinosaurs are known to have had low, narrow and elongated jaws with snout tips that fanned out into a [[Rosette (design)|rosette]]-like shape, similar to that of modern [[Gharial]]<nowiki/>s.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Fossil evidence shows that besides fish, spinosaurids also consumed pterosaurs and other dinosaurs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Martill|first2=David|last3=Escuilli\u00e9|first3=Fran\u00e7ois|date=2004-07-01|title=Pterosaurs as part of a spinosaur diet|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/430033a|journal=Nature|language=En|volume=429|issue=6995|pages=33|doi=10.1038/430033a|pmid=15229562|bibcode=2004Natur.429...33B|issn=0028-0836}}</ref> In the Sao Khua Formation, localities such as Wat Sakawan have yielded sauropod remains in association with tooth crowns from ''Siamosaurus'', documenting either predation or scavenging on part of the latter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n[[File:Spinosaurid_and_Kinnareemimus.PNG|thumb|Restoration of a generic spinosaur feeding on a [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] carcass in the [[Sao Khua Formation]] (''[[Kinnareemimus]]'' in the background), based on teeth belonging to ''Siamosaurus''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Lacerda|first2=Marcel B.|last3=Horn|first3=Bruno L. D.|last4=Oliveira|first4=Isabel A. P. de|last5=Schultz|first5=Cesar L.|date=2016-02-01|title=The \"\u03c7\" of the Matter: Testing the Relationship between Paleoenvironments and Three Theropod Clades|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=11|issue=2|pages=e0147031|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147031|pmid=26829315|pmc=4734717|issn=1932-6203|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147031S}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2006, Thai biologist Komsorn Lauprasert examined fossils collected from the Phu Kradung, Sao Khua, and Khok Kruat Formations. In this study, the teeth of ''Siamosaurus'' and a Morrocan spinosaurid were compared to those of crocodilians using [[Scanning electron microscope|scanning electron microscopy]]. Lauprasert found that spinosaurids and crocodilians may have employed similar feeding tactics and been under comparable [[Constraint (classical mechanics)|mechanical constraints]], based on resemblances in the [[microstructure]] of their tooth enamel. Lauprasert suggested that ''Siamosaurus'' could have therefore replaced the [[ecological niche]] of contemporaneous long-snouted crocodilians as a piscivorous predator. He notes that this likely occurred in correlation with the rising aridity of the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations during the Early Cretaceous, since ''Siamosaurus'' had better mobility in a dry environment than crocodilians did. This could explain the absence of long-snouted crocodilian fossils from that time and place.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite thesis|last=Lauprasert|first=Komsorn|title=Evolution and palaeoecology of crocodiles in the mesozoic of Khorat plateau, Thailand|date=2006|publisher=Chulalongkorn University|url=https://cuir.car.chula.ac.th/handle/123456789/14411|language=en}}</ref> A similar scenario was proposed for spinosaurids by Hone and colleagues in 2010, who noted that compared to large crocodilians and obligate aquatic predators, they could more easily travel from one body of water to another in search for prey.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n=== Aquatic habits ===\n\nA 2010 publication by French palaeontologist Romain Amiot and colleagues found that the [[isotopes of oxygen|oxygen isotope]] ratios of spinosaurid bones indicated [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles. Isotope ratios of spinosaurid teeth from various localities, including Thailand and China, were compared with isotopic compositions from contemporaneous theropods, turtles, and crocodilians. The study revealed that, among theropods, spinosaurid isotope ratios were closer to those of turtles and crocodilians. Thai spinosaurid teeth tended to have the largest difference from the ratios of other theropods, and those from Morocco tended to have the least difference. The authors concluded that spinosaurids, like modern crocodilians and hippopotamuses, spent much of their daily lives in or near water. They also suggested that semiaquatic habits and piscivory may explain how spinosaurids coexisted with other large theropods; by feeding on different prey items and occupying a distinct ecological niche, the different types of theropods would have been out of direct competition.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\"RMetal10\">{{cite journal |last=Amiot |first=R. |author2=Buffetaut, E. |author3=L\u00e9cuyer, C. |author4=Wang, X. |author5=Boudad, L. |author6=Ding, Z. |author7=Fourel, F. |author8=Hutt, S. |author9=Martineau, F. |author10=Medeiros, A. |author11=Mo, J. |author12=Simon, L. |author13=Suteethorn, V. |author14=Sweetman, S. |author15=Tong, H. |author16=Zhang, F. |author17=Zhou, Z. |year=2010 |title=Oxygen isotope evidence for semi-aquatic habits among spinosaurid theropods |journal=Geology |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=139\u2013142 |doi=10.1130/G30402.1|bibcode=2010Geo....38..139A }}</ref>\n\n== Palaeoenvironment and palaeobiogeography ==\n[[File:Sao_Khua_Formation_V2.png|thumb|left|Restoration of ''Siamosaurus'' hunting fish in the Sao Khua Formation, with a herd of ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]]'' in the background]]\n\nThe sediments of the Sao Khua Formation, composed of [[Red clay|red clays]], [[Mudstone|mudstones]], [[Sandstone|sandstones]], [[Siltstone|siltstones]] and [[Conglomerate (geology)|conglomerate]] rocks, record a [[fluvial]] environment dominated by lakes, [[Floodplain|floodplains]], and meandering low-energy rivers.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> This is consistent with the types of vertebrate fauna present in the formation, which comprise only terrestrial or freshwater animals, including dinosaurs, turtles, freshwater [[hybodont sharks]] and [[Actinopterygii|actinopterygian]] fishes, and the freshwater crocodilian ''[[Sunosuchus]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> Besides ''Siamosaurus'', there were dinosaurs like the [[Metriacanthosauridae|metriacanthosaurid]] ''Siamotyrannus isanensis'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carrano|first1=M. T.|last2=Benson|first2=R. B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=S. D.|date=2012|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927}}</ref> the [[Ornithomimosauria|ornithomimosaur]] ''[[Kinnareemimus]] khonkaenensis'',<ref name=\"description\">Buffetaut, E., Suteethorn, V. and Tong, H. (2009). \"An early 'ostrich dinosaur' (Theropoda: Ornithomimosauria) from the Early Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of NE Thailand\", pp. 229-243 IN E. Buffetaut, G. Cuny, J. Le Loeuff & V. Suteethorn (eds.), ''Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Ecosystems in SE Asia''. Geological Society, London, Special Publications 315: 229-243. {{doi|10.1144/SP315.16}}</ref> the [[Megaraptora|megaraptoran]] ''[[Phuwiangvenator]]'' ''yaemniyomi'', the basal [[Coelurosauria|coelurosaur]] ''[[Vayuraptor]]'' ''nongbualamphuensis,<ref name=\"Samathietal2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=A.|last2=Chanthasit|first2=P.|last3=Martin Sander|first3=P.|date=May 2019|title=Two new basal coelurosaurian theropod dinosaurs from the Lower Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of Thailand|journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica|language=en|volume=64|issue=2|pages=239\u2013260|doi=10.4202/app.00540.2018}}</ref>'' a ''[[Compsognathus]]''-like theropod, as well as sauropods like ''Phuwiangosaurus sirindhornae'' and two indeterminate forms. Sauropod remains are some of the most abundant in the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> No [[Ornithischia|ornithischian]] dinosaur fossils have been found in the Sao Khua Formation, possibly suggesting that they were uncommon compared to [[Saurischia|saurischian]] dinosaurs.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations had a more [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] climate than the older, more humid [[Phu Kradung Formation]].<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe Khok Kruat Formation is composed mostly of sandstones, conglomerates, siltstones, and [[Shale|shales]]. Similarly to the Sao Khua Formation, the deposition of these sediments occurred in an arid to semi-arid floodplain environment of slow-moving, meandering rivers.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=Jintasakul|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|last4=You|first4=Hai-Lu|date=2015|title=A New Basal Hadrosauroid Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation in Nakhon Ratchasima Province, Northeastern Thailand|url=|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=10|issue=12|pages=e0145904|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1045904S|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0145904|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4696827|pmid=26716981|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":12\" /> Vertebrates from the Khok Kruat assemblage include [[Semionotiformes|semionotiform]] fishes, hybodont sharks, turtles, dinosaurs, pterosaurs, and crocodilians. The dinosaur fauna of this ecosystem included the [[Carcharodontosauridae|carcharodontosaurid]] ''[[Siamraptor]]'' ''suwati'',''<ref name=\"Chokchaloemwong2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Chokchaloemwong|first=Duangsuda|last2=Hattori|first2=Soki|last3=Cuesta|first3=Elena|last4=Jintasakul|first4=Pratueng|last5=Shibata|first5=Masateru|last6=Azuma|first6=Yoichi|date=2019-10-09|editor-last=Liu|editor-first=Jun|title=A new carcharodontosaurian theropod (Dinosauria: Saurischia) from the Lower Cretaceous of Thailand|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=14|issue=10|pages=e0222489|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0222489|pmid=31596853|pmc=6784982|issn=1932-6203}}</ref>'' [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontians]] like ''[[Sirindhorna]] khoratensis'',<ref name=\":15\" /> ''[[Ratchasimasaurus]] suranaerae'',<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=JINTASAKUL|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|date=2011-10-01|title=A New Iguanodontian Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation, Nakhon Ratchasima in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/264655916|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica|volume=85|issue=5|pages=969\u2013976|doi=10.1111/j.1755-6724.2011.00530.x}}</ref> and ''[[Siamodon]] nimngami'';<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2011-01-01|title=A new iguanodontian dinosaur from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous, Aptian) of northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396911000425|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|language=en|volume=97|issue=1\u20132|pages=51\u201362|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2011.08.001|issn=0753-3969|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh}}</ref> as well as a ''Phuwiangosaurus''-like sauropod,<ref name=\":7\" /> an indeterminate [[Ceratopsia|ceratopsian]],<ref name=\"sereno2010\">{{cite book|title=New Perspectives on Horned Dinosaurs: The Royal Tyrrell Museum Ceratopsian Symposium|last=Sereno|first=Paul C.|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2010|editor1-last=Ryan|editor1-first=Michael J.|location=Bloomington and Indianapolis|pages=21\u201358|chapter=Taxonomy, cranial morphology, and relationships of parrot-beaked dinosaurs (Ceratopsia:''Psittacosaurus'')|editor2-last=Chinnery-Allgeier|editor2-first=Brenda J.|editor3-last=Eberth|editor3-first=David A.}}</ref> and various indeterminate theropods.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> The formation is probably equivalent to the [[Gres superieurs Formation]] of Laos, since animals like advanced iguanodontians, sauropods, and spinosaurids have also been found there.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\nIn 2010, American palaeontologist [[Stephen L. Brusatte|Stephen Brusatte]] and colleagues noted that the discovery of spinosaurids in Asia, a family previously known only from Europe, Africa, and South America, suggests faunal interchange between the [[Supercontinent|supercontinents]] [[Laurasia]] (in the north) and [[Gondwana]] (in the south) during the early Late Cretaceous. Though it may also be possible that spinosaurids already had a [[cosmopolitan distribution]] before the Middle Cretaceous, and thus preceding the breakup of Laurasia from Gondwana. However, the authors noted that more evidence is needed to test this hypothesis.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Brusatte|first=Stephen|last2=B. J. Benson|first2=R|last3=Xu|first3=Xing|date=2010-12-10|title=The evolution of large-bodied therood dinosaurs during the Mesozoic in Asia|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260714806|journal=Journal of Iberian Geology|volume=36|issue=2|pages=275\u2013296|doi=10.5209/rev_JIGE.2010.v36.n2.12}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n{{Megalosauroidea}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q134636}}\n\n[[Category:Spinosaurids]]\n[[Category:Barremian life]]\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1986]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by \u00c9ric Buffetaut]]\n", "name_user": "Logo8th", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siamosaurus"}
{"title_page": "Sir Robert Gordon, 1st Baronet", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:Sir Robert Gordon 1621.jpg|thumb|Sir Robert Gordon, 1621 portrait]]\n'''Sir Robert Gordon of Gordonstoun''' (1580\u20131656) was a Scottish politician and courtier, known as the historian of the noble house of Sutherland.\n\n==Life==\nBorn at [[Dunrobin Castle]], [[Golspie]], [[Sutherland]], on 14 May 1580, he was the fourth son of Alexander Gordon, 12th [[Earl of Sutherland]], by his second wife [[Jean Gordon, Countess of Bothwell]]. In 1598 he was sent to the [[University of St. Andrews]], where he remained six months, and then finished his education in Edinburgh. In January 1603 he went to France to study [[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]], and remained there until October 1605.<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Gordon, Robert (1580-1656)|volume=22}}</ref>\n\nGordon was appointed a gentleman of the privy chamber to James I in 1606, and was knighted. On 16 July 1614 he received a grant of holdings in Ulster. In March 1614-15, having attended the king to Cambridge, he was created honorary M.A. On the death of his brother [[John Gordon, 13th Earl of Sutherland|John, 12th or 13th Earl of Sutherland]], in September of the same year, he became tutor at law of his nephew John Gordon, 13th [[Earl of Sutherland]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nIn 1617 King James visited Scotland for the first time after his accession to the English throne. Among the entertainments was a competition of archery in the garden of [[Holyrood Palace]], at which Gordon gained the prize, a silver arrow. He remained in Scotland for some time, and having settled his affairs in Sutherland, he returned with his family to England in November 1619, and in the succeeding May revisited France, when he disposed of his property of Longorme to Walter Stewart. In 1621 he returned to Sutherland, when he relieved the estates of the earl of a heavy burden of debt.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nIn 1623, when George Sinclair, 5th [[Earl of Caithness]] was proclaimed a rebel, and fled to the Orkney Islands, Gordon received a commission from the privy council to proceed with fire and sword against him, and took possession of [[Castle Sinclair]], the earl's residence. Having subdued the county of Caithness, he returned with his troops into Sutherland, and soon after went back to the court in England (and probably on to France).<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nIn 1624 Gordon was appointed one of the commissioners of the estates of the young [[James Stewart, 1st Duke of Richmond|Duke of Lennox]], and two years later one of the duke's curators. On 28 May 1625, then a gentleman of the privy chamber to Charles I, he was created premier [[baronet of Nova Scotia]], with remainder to his heir male whatsoever; and he obtained a charter under the great seal granting to him sixteen thousand acres on the coast of [[Nova Scotia]], which were erected into a barony. He assisted under agreement [[Sir William Alexander of Menstrie]] in the plantation of a colony in Nova Scotia. A favourite of King Charles, he was employed as confidential messenger to [[Henrietta Maria]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nIn August 1629 Gordon was chosen sheriff principal of [[Inverness-shire]], and represented the shire at the convention of 1630. In May 1630 he was sent by the lords of the council along with Sir William Seton into the north to quell some disturbances. On 13 July in the same year James, Duke of Lennox, as [[lord high chamberlain of Scotland]], appointed him his vice-chamberlain during his absence in France. At the coronation of Charles I in Scotland in 1633, he, as vice-chamberlain, with four earls' sons, carried the king's train from the castle to the abbey. The next year he was placed on the privy council in Scotland.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nOn 1 May 1639 Gordon was with the court at [[Durham, England|Durham]]; during the [[First English Civil War]]  acted as a mediator between the opposing parties. The gentry of [[Morayshire]] in 1643 appointed him, along with Thomas McKenzie of Pluscarden and John Innes of Leuchars, to confer with the [[James Graham, 1st Marquess of Montrose|Marquis of Montrose]]. His mother was persecuted as a Roman Catholic, and towards the end of her days excommunicated; in 1627 Gordon, to have the sentence relaxed, undertook a formal bond to the Bishop of Caithness that his mother would shun Catholic priests, and his own orthodoxy was probably suspect. In 1646, however, the presbytery of Elgin granted a testimonial in his favour. Gordon died in 1656.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Works==\nHis father-in-law Bishop Gordon, at his death in September 1619, left to Gordon the task of publishing his works, in English and Latin.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nGordon's ''Genealogical History of the Earldom of Sutherland, from its Origin to the year 1630'' (with a continuation to 1651 by Gilbert Gordon of Sallach) was edited by [[Henry William Weber]] from the original manuscript held by the [[Elizabeth Leveson-Gower, Duchess of Sutherland|Marchioness of Stafford]], later Duchess of Sutherland, and published at Edinburgh, 1813. A catalogue of Gordon's library was published in 1816; and the documents he collected, including his will dated 11 July 1654, were detailed in the 6th Report of the Historical Manuscripts Commission. Some were printed at length in Edward Dunbar Dunbar, ''Social Life in Former Days'', two series, 1865-6.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Family==\nGordon married at London, 16 February 1613, Louise, or Lucie, born 20 December 1597, only child of [[John Gordon (bishop)|John Gordon]], with whom he received the lordships of Glenluce in Scotland and of Longorme in France.  He had issue five sons and four daughters, including his eldest son, Sir Ludovick Gordon (1614\u201385) and a daughter Katherine (1621\u201383), married to [[David Barclay (Quaker)|Colonel David Barclay]]. He was the founder of the Morayshire family of Gordonstoun. Having acquired various estates in the shires of Elgin and Forres, he had them all united into the barony of [[Gordonstoun]], by a charter under the great seal, dated 20 June 1642.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Will==\nGordon's bequests included; to his eldest son Ludovick, his insignia as a knight baronet; to Ludovick's son Robert Gordon, a cup, his whalebone chessmen, and a suite of furniture of a green bed and couch worked in tent stitch made bt his mother-in-law Genevieve Petau; to his grandson Robert Barclay his silver coins; his wife Louise Gordon should leave the diamond jewel with the portrait of King James, that had belonged to her mother ([[Genevi\u00e8ve Petau de Maulette]]) who taught French to [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia]], to Ludovick and his son; his wife and Ludovick should continue building the church of Drenie, especially because they had demolished the church of Kinneddor.<ref>''HMC 6th Report (Sir W. G. Gordon Cumming)'' (London, 1877), p. 683.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n \n'''Attribution'''<!--Please do not reformat, for the sake of those using screen-readers-->\n \n{{DNB|wstitle=Gordon, Robert (1580-1656)|volume=22}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gordon, Robert}}\n[[Category:1580 births]]\n[[Category:1656 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Scottish genealogists]]\n[[Category:Scottish antiquarians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Convention of the Estates of Scotland 1630]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Shire Commissioners to the Parliament of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:Scottish historians]]\n[[Category:17th-century historians]]\n[[Category:People from Sutherland]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Scottish knights]]\n[[Category:Scottish legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|dat