, by a charter under the great seal, dated 20 June 1642.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Will==\nGordon's bequests included; to his eldest son Ludovick, his insignia as a knight baronet; to Ludovick's son Robert Gordon, a cup, his whalebone chessmen, and a suite of furniture of a green bed and couch worked in tent stitch made bt his mother-in-law Genevieve Petau; to his grandson Robert Barclay his silver coins; his wife Louise Gordon should leave the diamond jewel with the portrait of King James, that had belonged to her mother ([[Genevi\u00e8ve Petau de Maulette]]) who taught French to [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia]], to Ludovick and his son; his wife and Ludovick should continue building the church of Drenie, especially because they had demolished the church of Kinneddor.<ref>''HMC 6th Report (Sir W. G. Gordon Cumming)'' (London, 1877), p. 683.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n \n'''Attribution'''<!--Please do not reformat, for the sake of those using screen-readers-->\n \n{{DNB|wstitle=Gordon, Robert (1580-1656)|volume=22}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gordon, Robert}}\n[[Category:1580 births]]\n[[Category:1656 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Scottish genealogists]]\n[[Category:Scottish antiquarians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Convention of the Estates of Scotland 1630]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Shire Commissioners to the Parliament of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:Scottish historians]]\n[[Category:17th-century historians]]\n[[Category:People from Sutherland]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Scottish knights]]\n[[Category:Scottish legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Robert_Gordon,_1st_Baronet"}
